{"title_page": "Something Unforgivable", "text_new": "{{Infobox television episode\n| title          = Something Unforgivable\n| series         = [[Better Call Saul]]\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| season         = 5\n| episode        = 10\n| editor         = \n| airdate        = {{Start date|2020|4|20}}\n| writer         = Peter Gould<br />Ariel Levine\n| director       = [[Peter Gould]]\n| length         = 60 minutes\n| guests         = \n* Javier Grajeda as [[Juan Bolsa]]\n* [[Steven Bauer]] as [[Don Eladio Vuente]]\n* [[Roy Wood Jr.]] as Grant\n| music          = \n| prev           = [[Bad Choice Road]]\n| next           = \n| episode_list   = List of Better Call Saul episodes\n| season_article = Better Call Saul (season 5)\n}}\n\n\"'''Something Unforgivable'''\" is the tenth and final episode of the [[Better Call Saul (season 5)|fifth season]] of the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] television series ''[[Better Call Saul]]'', the spinoff series of ''[[Breaking Bad]]''. The episode aired on April 20, 2020 on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] in the United States. Outside of the United States, the episode premiered on streaming service [[Netflix]] in several countries.\n\n== Plot ==\nKIm and Jimmy watch Lalo leave. Jimmy asks Mike for details about why Mike has been protecting him, but Mike hangs up. Jimmy tells Kim the truth about his desert trek with Mike. Kim and Jimmy check into a downtown hotel for their safety.\n\nMike tells Gus that Lalo and Nacho went to Lalo's [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]] home. Gus tells Mike he has sent assassins after Lalo and suggests Nacho can help them. Lalo and Nacho arrive at Lalo's house and are warmly greeted by family and friends. Nacho receives a call telling him to open Lalo's back gate at 3 a.m.\n\nKim ignores Jimmy's request to remain at the hotel and visits the courthouse. She meets with the public defender and accepts 20 pending felony cases ''pro bono''. She tells Howard she quit Schweikart and Cokely. Howard warns Kim about Jimmy's recent harassment and suggests Kim should stop following his lead. Kim laughs at him and says she is insulted by the notion that she cannot decide for herself. As she leaves, Howard tells her that Chuck was the person who best understood Jimmy.\n\nLalo prepares Nacho for his first meeting with Don Eladio. At the meeting, Lalo explains that Nacho is associated with Tuco and will manage the Salamanca drug business while Lalo is in Mexico. Eladio is impressed with Nacho's plans to expand the Salamanca territory and gives his blessing.\n\nJimmy goes to Mike's house and demands that Mike explain why Mike has been aiding him. Mike reveals that Lalo will be killed that night, and Jimmy informs Kim. Kim an Jimmy discuss forcing a resolution of the Sandpiper case by sabotaging Howard, which would enable Jimmy to receive his seven-figure share of the settlement. Jimmy counsels against it, but Kim makes use of the same finger pointing gesture Jimmy previously used to show that she is serious about undermining Howard.{{efn|This is a reversal of the roles from the final scene of the fourth season finale episode \"[[Winner (Better Call Saul)|Winner]]\", when Jimmy reveals to Kim he plans to practice law under the name \"Saul Goodman\" and gives her the same gesture as he walks off.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-recaps/better-call-saul-season-5-finale-recap-something-unforgivable-984335/ |title=\u2018Better Call Saul\u2019 Season 5 Finale Recap: Survival Skills |last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |authorlink=Alan Sepinwall |date=April 20, 2020 |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/better-call-saul-season-5-finale-bob-odenkirk-rhea-seehorn/ |title=Better Call Saul finale: Bob Odenkirk and Rhea Seehorn break down Kim's shocking pitch to Jimmy |last=Snierson |first=Dan |date=April 20, 2020 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>}}\n\nLalo is awake at 3 a.m, so Nacho sets a fire as a distraction that enables him to open the gate. The assassins enter as Nacho flees, and Lalo kills all but one. He then instructs the survivor to call the middleman who arranged for the murder and report that Lalo was killed.\n\n== Production ==\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Ratings ===\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.amc.com/shows/better-call-saul/season-5/episode-10-something-unforgivable \"Something Unforgivable\"] at [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]\n*{{IMDb episode|8772224}}\n\n{{Better Call Saul}}\n\n[[Category:Better Call Saul (season 5) episodes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television episode\n| title          = Something Unforgivable\n| series         = [[Better Call Saul]]\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| season         = 5\n| episode        = 10\n| editor         = \n| airdate        = {{Start date|2020|4|20}}\n| writer         = Peter Gould<br />Ariel Levine\n| director       = [[Peter Gould]]\n| length         = 60 minutes\n| guests         = \n* Javier Grajeda as [[Juan Bolsa]]\n* [[Steven Bauer]] as [[Don Eladio Vuente]]\n* [[Roy Wood Jr.]] as Grant\n| music          = \n| prev           = [[Bad Choice Road]]\n| next           = \n| episode_list   = List of Better Call Saul episodes\n| season_article = Better Call Saul (season 5)\n}}\n\n\"'''Something Unforgivable'''\" is the tenth and final episode of the [[Better Call Saul (season 5)|fifth season]] of the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] television series ''[[Better Call Saul]]'', the spinoff series of ''[[Breaking Bad]]''. The episode aired on April 20, 2020 on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] in the United States. Outside of the United States, the episode premiered on streaming service [[Netflix]] in several countries.\n\n== Plot ==\nKIm and Jimmy watch Lalo leave. Jimmy asks Mike for details about why Mike has been protecting him, but Mike hangs up. Jimmy tells Kim the truth about his desert trek with Mike. Kim and Jimmy check into a downtown hotel for their safety.\n\nMike tells Gus that Lalo and Nacho went to Lalo's [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]] home. Gus tells Mike he has sent assassins after Lalo and suggests Nacho can help them. Lalo and Nacho arrive at Lalo's house and are warmly greeted by family and friends. Nacho receives a call telling him to open Lalo's back gate at 3 a.m.\n\nKim ignores Jimmy's request to remain at the hotel and visits the courthouse. She meets with the public defender and accepts 20 pending felony cases ''pro bono''. She tells Howard she quit Schweikart and Cokely. Howard warns Kim about Jimmy's recent harassment and suggests Kim should stop following his lead. Kim laughs at him and says she is insulted by the notion that she cannot decide for herself. As she leaves, Howard tells her that Chuck was the person who best understood Jimmy.\n\nLalo prepares Nacho for his first meeting with Don Eladio. At the meeting, Lalo explains that Nacho is associated with Tuco and will manage the Salamanca drug business while Lalo is in Mexico. Eladio is impressed with Nacho's plans to expand the Salamanca territory and gives his blessing.\n\nJimmy goes to Mike's house and demands that Mike explain why Mike has been aiding him. Mike reveals that Lalo will be killed that night, and Jimmy informs Kim. Kim an Jimmy discuss forcing a resolution of the Sandpiper case by sabotaging Howard, which would enable Jimmy to receive his seven-figure share of the settlement. Jimmy counsels against it, but Kim makes use of the same finger pointing gesture Jimmy used when telling her he intended to practice law as Saul Goodman to show that she is serious about undermining Howard.{{efn|This is a reversal of the roles from the final scene of the fourth season finale episode \"[[Winner (Better Call Saul)|Winner]]\", when Jimmy reveals to Kim he plans to practice law under the name \"Saul Goodman\" and gives her the same gesture as he walks off.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-recaps/better-call-saul-season-5-finale-recap-something-unforgivable-984335/ |title=\u2018Better Call Saul\u2019 Season 5 Finale Recap: Survival Skills |last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |authorlink=Alan Sepinwall |date=April 20, 2020 |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/better-call-saul-season-5-finale-bob-odenkirk-rhea-seehorn/ |title=Better Call Saul finale: Bob Odenkirk and Rhea Seehorn break down Kim's shocking pitch to Jimmy |last=Snierson |first=Dan |date=April 20, 2020 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>}}\n\nLalo is awake at 3 a.m, so Nacho sets a fire as a distraction that enables him to open the gate. The assassins enter as Nacho flees, and Lalo kills all but one. He then instructs the survivor to call the middleman who arranged for the murder and report that Lalo was killed.\n\n== Production ==\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Ratings ===\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.amc.com/shows/better-call-saul/season-5/episode-10-something-unforgivable \"Something Unforgivable\"] at [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]\n*{{IMDb episode|8772224}}\n\n{{Better Call Saul}}\n\n[[Category:Better Call Saul (season 5) episodes]]\n", "name_user": "Billmckern", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Something_Unforgivable"}
{"title_page": "Alain de Benoist", "text_new": "{{short description|French journalist and political theorist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox philosopher\n| image         = 20110402 De Benoist.png\n| caption       = Alain de Benoist in 2012\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1943|12|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Tours]], [[Indre-et-Loire]], [[France]]\n| alias         = Fabrice Laroche, Robert de Herte, David Barney\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Paris]]\n| occupation    = Journalist, essayist \n| relatives     = [[Gustave Moreau]] (great-granduncle)<ref>Michael B\u00f6hm, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Ty_MBj109EQC&dq= ''Alain de Benoist und die Nouvelle Droite''], LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster, 2008, p. 47.</ref>\n| years_active  = 1960\u2013present\n| school_tradition = ''[[Nouvelle Droite]]''\n| notable_ideas= Modernization and secularization of Christian Values, Repaganization of the West, [[Pens\u00e9e unique]], [[Nouvelle Droite]], [[Ethnopluralism]]\n| influences    = [[Johann Gottfried Herder|Herder]], [[Carl Schmitt|Schmitt]], [[Antonio Gramsci|Gramsci]], [[Julius Evola|Evola]], [[Friedrich Nietzsche|Nietzsche]], [[Louis Dumont|Dumont]], [[Martin Heidegger|Heidegger]], [[Jean Baudrillard|Baudrillard]], [[Oswald Spengler|Spengler]], [[Ernst J\u00fcnger|J\u00fcnger]], [[Giorgio Locchi|Locchi]], [[Georges Dum\u00e9zil|Dum\u00e9zil]], [[Jos\u00e9 Ortega y Gasset|Ortega y Gasset]], [[Vilfredo Pareto|Pareto]], [[Alasdair MacIntyre|MacIntyre]], [[Charles Taylor (philosopher)|Taylor]], [[Martin Buber|Buber]], [[Karl Marx|Marx]]\n| influenced    = [[Guillaume Faye]], [[Marco Tarchi]], [[Patrice de Plunkett]], [[Dragoslav Bokan]], [[Martin A. Lee]], [[Pat Buchanan]], [[Aleksandr Dugin]]\n}}\n\n'''Alain de Benoist de Gentissart''' ({{IPAc-en|d|\u0259|_|b|\u0259|\u02c8|n|w|\u0251\u02d0}}; {{IPA-fr|d\u0259 b\u0259nwa|lang}}; born 11 December 1943), also known as Fabrice Laroche, Robert de Herte and other aliases,<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=UUSCDwAAQBAJ|title=Key Thinkers of the Radical Right: Behind the New Threat to Liberal Democracy|last=Sedgwick|first=Mark|date=8 January 2019|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190877613|pages=74\u201375|language=en}}</ref> is a [[French people|French]] journalist and political philosopher, a founding member of the [[Nouvelle Droite]] (\"New Right\"), and the leader of the [[Ethnic nationalism|ethno-nationalist]] think tank [[Groupement de recherche et d'\u00e9tudes pour la civilisation europ\u00e9enne|GRECE]].\n\nPrincipally influenced by thinkers of the [[Conservative Revolution|German Conservative Revolution]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=N5KoDQAAQBAJ|title=Where Have All The Fascists Gone?|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|date=5 December 2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351873130|pages=340|language=en}}</ref> de Benoist is opposed to [[Christianity]], the [[Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen|rights of man]], [[neoliberalism]], [[representative democracy]], [[egalitarianism]]; and what he sees as embodying and promoting those values, namely the [[United States]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|title=Intellectual Right \u2013 Wing Extremism \u2013 Alain de Benoist's Mazeway Resynthesis since 2000|date=7 December 2011|work=The Extreme Right in Europe|pages=335|editor-last=Backes|editor-first=Uwe|edition=1|publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht|language=en|doi=10.13109/9783666369223.333|isbn=9783525369227|quote=De Benoist\u2019s continued anti-egalitarianism, rejection of the Rights of Man and representative democracy, as well as valorization of pagan elite rule [...]|editor2-last=Moreau|editor2-first=Patrick|chapter=Intellectual Right - Wing Extremism \u2013 Alain de Benoist's Mazeway Resynthesis since 2000}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Trouble on the right; recent gains by the extreme-right leader Jean-Marie Le Pen have left conservatives and moderates confused about whether to imitate or attack him; France The Atlantic February 1985</ref><ref>{{cite book|quote=In contrast, on this side of the Atlantic, a liberal is primarily a spokesman of individualism, a supporter of free trade, and an opponent of the state (and also a supporter of America).|first=Alain|last=de Benoist|chapter=Preface: The New Right: Forty Years After|editor-first=Tomislav|editor-last=Sunic|title=Against Democracy and Equality|isbn=978-1-907166-25-9|year=2011}}</ref> He theorized the notion of [[ethnopluralism]], a concept which relies on preserving and mutually respecting individual and bordered ethno-cultural regions.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|date=2001|title=The Ambiguities of the Nouvelle Droite, 1968\u20131999|journal=The European Legacy|volume=6|issue=3|pages=333\u2013351|doi=10.1080/10848770120051349|via=Taylor & Francis}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=McCulloch|first=Tom|date=1 August 2006|title=The Nouvelle Droite in the 1980s and 1990s: Ideology and Entryism, the Relationship with the Front National|journal=French Politics|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=158\u2013178|doi=10.1057/palgrave.fp.8200099|issn=1476-3419|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/2ed0f6b2f7b333ba7ff36154bfb9e394f49b0229}}</ref>\n\nHis work has been influential with the [[alt-right]] movement in the United States, and he presented a lecture on identity at a [[National Policy Institute]] conference hosted by [[Richard B. Spencer]]; however, he has distanced himself from the movement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/the-french-ideologues-who-inspired-the-alt-right|title=The French Ideologues Who Inspired the Alt-Right|last=Kennedy|first=Dana|date=30 January 2017|newspaper=The Daily Beast|access-date=22 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mohdin |first1=Aamna |title=The alt-right are targeting disgruntled white male lefties to join their movement |url=https://qz.com/1176355/how-richard-spencer-and-the-alt-right-are-adopting-left-wing-language-to-recruit-leftie-men/ |accessdate=23 August 2018 |work=Quartz |date=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n=== Early life (1943\u20131961) ===\n[[File:Blason famille fr Benoist.svg|thumb|[[Coat of arms]] of House de Benoist]]\nAlain de Benoist de Gentissart<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=_JNaHlYENu8C|title=Extr\u00e9mismes. enqu\u00eate sur une grande peur contemporaine|last=Bourseiller|first=Christophe|date=15 January 2012|publisher=CNRS|isbn=9782271073624|language=fr}}</ref> was born on 11 December 1943 in Saint-Symphorien (now part of [[Tours]]), [[Centre-Val de Loire]],<ref name=\":5\">{{Citation|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|title=Intellectual Right - Wing Extremism \u2013 Alain de Benoist's Mazeway Resynthesis since 2000|date=7 December 2011|work=The Extreme Right in Europe|pages=333\u2013340|editor-last=Backes|editor-first=Uwe|edition=1|publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht|language=en|doi=10.13109/9783666369223.333|isbn=9783525369227|editor2-last=Moreau|editor2-first=Patrick}}</ref> the son of a head of sales at [[Guerlain]], also named Alain de Benoist (1902\u20131971), and Germaine Langou\u00ebt (1908\u20131981).<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> De Benoist grew up in a bourgeois and [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] family.<ref name=\":7\" /> While his mother came from the lower-middle class of [[Normandy]] and [[Brittany]], his father allegedly belonged to the Belgian nobility.<ref name=\":11\" /> During [[World War II|WWII]], de Benoist's father was a member of the [[French resistance|resistance]] armed group [[French Forces of the Interior]]. He was a self-declared [[Gaullism|Gaullist]], while his wife Germaine was rather left-leaning;<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=t-lMZhdWxGoC|title=L'Europe en chemise noire: Les extr\u00eames droites europ\u00e9ennes de 1945 \u00e0 aujourd'hui|last=Milza|first=Pierre|date=4 September 2002|publisher=Fayard|isbn=9782213651064|language=fr}}</ref> and the de Benoist family divided between [[Free France]] and [[Vichy France]] during the war.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=OW_7pvGOxKUC|title=La Guerre d'Alg\u00e9rie et les intellectuels fran\u00e7ais|last=Rioux|first=Jean-Pierre|last2=Sirinelli|first2=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|date=1991|publisher=Editions Complexe|isbn=9782870273777|pages=61|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nDe Benoist was still in high school at [[Lyc\u00e9e Montaigne (Paris)|Lyc\u00e9e Montaigne]] and [[Lyc\u00e9e Louis-le-Grand|Louis-le-Grand]] during the turmoils of the [[Algerian War|Algerian war]] (1954-1962),<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=V3toDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT23|title=Les plastiqueurs: Une histoire secr\u00e8te de l'extr\u00eame droite violente|last=Charpier|first=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|date=23 August 2018|publisher=La D\u00e9couverte|isbn=9782348035579|pages=23|language=fr}}</ref> a moment that shaped his political views.<ref name=\":11\" /> In 1957 at 14, he met the daughter of the [[Antisemitism|antisemite]] journalist and [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theorist]] [[Henry Coston]], and began his journalist career three years later by writing for Henry Coston's magazine, ''Lectures Fran\u00e7aises.<ref name=\":7\" />''<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=938sDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA78|title=Hate: The Rising Tide of Anti-Semitism in France (and What It Means for Us)|last=Weitzmann|first=Marc|date=12 March 2019|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|isbn=9780544791343|pages=77\u201378|language=en}}</ref> De Benoist however stayed away from Coston\u2019s conspiracy theories on the [[Freemasonry]] and the Jews.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nAt 17 in 1961, he met [[Fran\u00e7ois d'Orcival]], with whom he became the editor of an underground newspaper for the pro-colonial paramilitary organisation [[Organisation arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te|OAS]], titled ''France Information''.<ref name=\":2\">Philippe Lamy (under the dir. of Claude Dargent), ''Le Club de l\u2019horloge (1974\u20132002): \u00e9volution et mutation d\u2019un laboratoire id\u00e9ologique'', Paris, universit\u00e9 Paris-VIII, 2016. p. 86, 97, 99 ([http://www.theses.fr/2016PA080034/document read online])</ref> The same year, he joined the student society [[Federation of Nationalist Students]] (FEN) and became in 1962 the secretary of the organization's magazine, ''Cahiers universitaires'', in which he wrote the main articles along with D'Orcival.''<ref name=\":7\" />''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=frhYDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT30|title=Vous avez dit fascismes ?|last=Taguieff|first=Pierre-Andr\u00e9|last2=Tarnero|first2=Jacques|last3=Badinter|first3=Robert|date=31 December 1983|publisher=FeniXX r\u00e9\u00e9dition num\u00e9rique|isbn=9782402119221|pages=30\u201333|language=fr}}</ref> As a student in law and literature, he began a period of political activism and passion for [[Fantastique|fantastique cinema]].<ref name=\":16\" /> According to [[Pierre-Andr\u00e9 Taguieff]] and [[Pierre Milza]], de Benoist had an intellectual curiosity that was lacking from his elder colleagues [[Dominique Venner]] (1935\u20132013) and [[Jean Mabire]] (1927\u20132006), and the young journalist led them to discover a conceptual universe \"that they could not imagine\", no more than its \"possible ideological exploitations\".<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Radical political activism (1962\u20131967) ===\nDe Benoist met [[Dominique Venner]] in 1962.''<ref name=\":7\" />'' The following year, he took part in the creation of ''[[Europe-Action]]'', a [[white nationalist]] magazine created by Venner in which he worked as a journalist.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=OW_7pvGOxKUC|title=La Guerre d'Alg\u00e9rie et les intellectuels fran\u00e7ais|last=Rioux|first=Jean-Pierre|last2=Sirinelli|first2=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|date=1991|publisher=Editions Complexe|isbn=9782870273777|pages=65\u201366|language=fr}}</ref> De Benoist published at that times his first essays: ''[[Raoul Salan|Salan]] devant l'opinion'' (\"Salan faces the (public) opinion\", 1963) and ''Le courage est leur patrie'' (\"Braveness is their motherland\", 1965), defending [[French Algeria]] and the [[Organisation arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te|OAS]].''<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":17\" />''\n\nBetween 1963 and 1965, de Benoist was a member of the [[Rationalist Union]] and likely began to read [[Louis Rougier]]'s [[criticism of Christianity]]\u2014who was also an adherent of the organization\u2014during this period. They maintained a relationship and Rougier's thesis deeply influenced de Benoist's own [[Criticism of Christianity|anti-Christianity]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=D1WwAAAAIAAJ|title=Sur la Nouvelle Droite: jalons d'une analyse critique|last=Taguieff|first=Pierre Andr\u00e9|date=1994|publisher=Descartes et Cie|isbn=9782910301026|pages=137|language=fr}}</ref> \"We oppose Rougier to [[Jean-Paul Sartre|Sartre]],\" de Benoist wrote in 1965, \"like we oppose verbal delirium to logics [...], because biologicial realism is the best support against those idealistic chimeras\".<ref name=\":7\" /> De Benoist continued his journalistic career and became in 1964 the editor-in-chief of the weekly publication ''[[Europe-Action]] Hebdomaire'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=g1JPDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT201|title=The French National Front: The Extremist Challenge To Democracy|last=Simmons|first=Harvey G.|date=5 March 2018|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780429976179|pages=201|language=en}}</ref> holding the same position at ''L'Observateur Europ\u00e9en'' from 1964 to 1968''.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Taguieff|first=Pierre-Andr\u00e9|date=1993|title=Origines et m\u00e9tamorphoses de la Nouvelle Droite|journal=Vingti\u00e8me Si\u00e8cle. Revue d'histoire|issue=40|pages=5\u20136|doi=10.2307/3770354|issn=0294-1759|jstor=3770354}}</ref>'' He also wrote in the [[neo-fascist]] magazine ''[[D\u00e9fense de l\u2019Occident|D\u00e9fense de l'Occident]]'', founded in 1952 by [[Maurice Bard\u00e8che]].<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nAfter a visit to [[South Africa]] at the invitation of [[Hendrik Verwoerd]]'s [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] government, de Benoist co-wrote with Gilles Fournier the 1965 essay ''V\u00e9rit\u00e9 pour l'Afrique du Sud'' (\"Truth for South Africa\"), in which they endorsed [[apartheid]].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=7eGJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA121|title=The Extreme Right in France: From P\u00e9tain to Le Pen|last=Shields|first=James|date=7 May 2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134861118|pages=121|language=en}}</ref> The following year, he co-wrote with D'Orcival another essay, ''Rhod\u00e9sie, pays des lions fid\u00e8les'' (\"Rhodesia, country of the faithful lions\", 1966), in defense of [[Rhodesia]], a breakaway country in southern Africa ruled by a white-minority government. The then prime minister of the [[List of historical unrecognized states and dependencies|unrecognised state]], [[Ian Smith]], prefaced the book.<ref name=\":10\" /> Returning from a trip to the [[United States]], de Benoist deplored the suppression of [[Racial segregation in the United States|racial segregation]] and wrote as a prediction that the system would survive outside the law, thus in a more violent way.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>Alain de Benoist: \"The legal segregation removed (and it will be removed everywhere, we must not be under any illusions) is immediately replaced by a ''de facto'' segregation over which the legal, and therefore peaceful, means have no more influence.\" (''Europe-Action'', octobre 1965 (34), <abbr>pp.</abbr> 9\u201312)</ref>\n\nIn two essays published in 1966, ''Les Indo-Europ\u00e9ens'' (\"The [[Proto-Indo-Europeans|Indo-Europeans]]\") and ''Qu'est-ce que le nationalisme?'' (\"What is nationalism?\"), de Benoist contributed to define a new [[Pan-European nationalism|European nationalism]], where the European civilization\u2014or the \"white race\"\u2014<ref name=\":15\">Alain de Benoist: \"Race is the only real unit encompassing individual variations. The objective study of history shows that only the European race (white race, caucasian) has continued to progress since its appearance on the rising path of the evolution of the living, unlike races stagnant in their development, therefore in virtual regression [...] The European race does not have absolute superiority. It is only the most capable of progressing in the direction of evolution [...] Racial factors being statistically hereditary, each race has its own psychology. All psychology generates value.\" (Qu'est-ce que le nationalisme?, 1966, pp. 8\u20139)</ref> would be considered above its constituting ethnic groups, all united in a common empire and civilization including [[Russia]]. This theory was embodied in the program of the [[European Rally for Liberty]] (REL), in which de Benoist was a member of the national council, during the [[1967 French legislative election|1967 legislative election]], and later became a core idea of GRECE in 1968.<ref name=\":82\">{{Cite journal|last=Taguieff|first=Pierre-Andr\u00e9|date=1993|title=Origines et m\u00e9tamorphoses de la Nouvelle Droite|journal=Vingti\u00e8me Si\u00e8cle. Revue d'histoire|issue=40|pages=4\u20136|doi=10.2307/3770354|issn=0294-1759|jstor=3770354}}</ref>\n\nThe successive electoral failures of far-right movements\u2014from that of presidential candidate [[Jean-Louis Tixier-Vignancour]] in 1965, who de Benoist had supported via the \"T.V. Committees\", to the debacle of the REL in March 1967,\u2014led de Benoist to question his political involvement and focus on a [[Metapolitics|meta-political]] strategy. In the fall of 1967, he decided to make a \"permanent and complete break with political action\" and to launch a review.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=_j5YDgAAQBAJ|title=Far-Right Politics in Europe|last=Camus|first=Jean-Yves|last2=Lebourg|first2=Nicolas|date=20 March 2017|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674971530|pages=132\u201333|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":82\" /> During the [[May 1968 events in France|May 1968 events]], then 25, he was a journalist for the [[professional magazine]] ''L'\u00c9cho de la presse et de la publicit\u00e9''.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\n=== Nouvelle Droite and media fame (1968\u20131993) ===\nAlong with militants of the REL and FEN, de Benoist founded in 1968 GRECE, an [[Ethnic nationalism|ethnonationalist]] [[think-tank]], of which he soon became the leader and its \"most authoritative spokesman\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Spektorowski|first=Alberto|date=1 February 2003|title=The New Right: Ethno-regionalism, ethno-pluralism and the emergence of a neo-fascist 'Third Way'|journal=Journal of Political Ideologies|volume=8|issue=1|pages=116|doi=10.1080/13569310306084|issn=1356-9317}}</ref><ref>Griffin, Roger (2000). \"Between Metapolitics and Apoliteia: the Nouvelle Droite's Strategy for Conserving the Fascist Vision in the 'Interregnum'\". Modern & Contemporary France. 8 (1): p. 35</ref> In the 1970s, de Benoist adapted his geopolitical view-points, from a pro-colonial attitude towards [[third-Worldism]];<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=OW_7pvGOxKUC|title=La Guerre d'Alg\u00e9rie et les intellectuels fran\u00e7ais|last=Rioux|first=Jean-Pierre|last2=Sirinelli|first2=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|date=1991|publisher=Editions Complexe|isbn=9782870273777|pages=76|language=fr}}</ref> from the defense of the \"last outposts of the West\" towards [[Anti-Americanism|anti-americanism]];<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=D1WwAAAAIAAJ|title=Sur la Nouvelle Droite: jalons d'une analyse critique|last=Taguieff|first=Pierre Andr\u00e9|date=1994|publisher=Descartes et Cie|isbn=9782910301026|pages=300|language=fr}}</ref> and from a biological to a cultural definition of \"difference\", developed in his [[Ethnopluralism|ethnopluralist]] theories.<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite journal|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|date=1 June 2001|title=The Ambiguities of the Nouvelle Droite, 1968\u20131999|journal=The European Legacy|volume=6|issue=3|pages=339|doi=10.1080/10848770120051349|issn=1084-8770}}</ref>\n\nHis works, along with others published by the think tank, led what media called the \"[[Nouvelle Droite]]\" to fame in the late 1970s.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|date=1 June 2001|title=The Ambiguities of the Nouvelle Droite, 1968\u20131999|journal=The European Legacy|volume=6|issue=3|pages=333\u2013334|doi=10.1080/10848770120051349|issn=1084-8770}}</ref> De Benoist became a critic for mainstream right-wing magazines, namely ''[[Valeurs actuelles|Valeurs Actuelles]]'' (from 1970 to 1982) and ''[[Le Figaro Magazine]]'' (from 1977 to 1992),<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=XqoUAQAAIAAJ&q|title=Encyclop\u00e9die politique fran\u00e7aise|last=Ratier|first=Emmanuel|date=1 January 1992|publisher=Faits et documents|isbn=9782909769004|pages=73|language=fr}}</ref> and received in 1978 the [[Prix de l'essai]] from the [[Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]] for his book ''Vu de droite: Anthologie critique des id\u00e9es contemporaines'', which sold 30,000 copies.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=WbTEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT313|title=G\u00e9n\u00e9ration Occident|last=Charpier|first=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|date=31 January 2014|publisher=Le Seuil|isbn=9782021157512|pages=313|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nAlthough de Benoist has stated his retirement from political parties and elections to rather focus on [[Metapolitics|meta-politics]] dates back to 1968,<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>Johnson, Douglas (1995). \"The New Right in France\". In: Luciano Cheles, Ronnie Ferguson, and Michalina Vaughan (eds.) ''The Far Right in Western and Eastern Europe'' (second ed.). London and New York: Longman Group. pp. 238\u2013239</ref> he was a candidate for the far-right micro-party [[Party of New Forces]] during the [[1979 European Parliament election|1979 European elections]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=dqiFAAAAIAAJ|title=Visages de la Nouvelle droite: le GRECE et son histoire|last=Duranton-Crabol|first=Anne-Marie|date=1988|publisher=Presses de la Fondation nationale des sciences politiques|isbn=9782724605617|pages=124|language=fr}}</ref> In the [[1984 European Parliament election in France|1984 election to the European Parliament]], he announced his intention to vote for the [[French Communist Party]], and justified his choice by defining the party as the most credible anti-capitalist, anti-liberal, and anti-American political force then active in France.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|date=1 June 2001|title=The Ambiguities of the Nouvelle Droite, 1968\u20131999|journal=The European Legacy|volume=6|issue=3|pages=343|doi=10.1080/10848770120051349|issn=1084-8770}}</ref>\n\nDe Benoist met [[Aleksandr Dugin|Alexandr Dugin]] in 1989. They soon became close collaborators: de Benoist was invited to Moscow by Dugin in 1992, and the latter presented himself as the correspondent of GRECE in Moscow for a time. The two authors eventually broke their relationship in 1993 after a virulent campaign in French and German media against the \"[[National Bolshevism|red and brown]] threat\" in Russia. While de Benoist acknowledged ideological differences on [[Eurasianism]] and [[Martin Heidegger|Heidegger]], the two of them have maintained regular exchanges since then.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=Coi8BAAAQBAJ|title=In the Tracks of Breivik: Far Right Networks in Northern and Eastern Europe|last=Deland|first=Mats|last2=Minkenberg|first2=Michael|last3=Mays|first3=Christin|date=2014|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|isbn=9783643905420|pages=93\u201394|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Intellectual re-emergence (1994\u2013present) ===\nIn 1979 and 1993, two press campaigns launched in French liberal media against de Benoist,  claiming that he was a \"closet Fascist\" or a \"Nazi\", damaged his reputation and influence in France. They accused him of hiding his racist and anti-egalitarian beliefs in a seemingly acceptable way to the public, by replacing the hierarchy of races with the less suspicious concept of \"[[Ethnopluralism|ethno-pluralism]]\".<ref name=\":11\" /> Although he still frequently comments on politics, de Benoist chose in the early 1990s to focus on his intellectual activity and avoid media attention.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nSince the 2000s onward however, public interest for his works have re-emerged:<ref name=\":5\" /> he has made several media appearances in [[France Culture]], [[Europe 1]], [[Telemadrid]], [[Radio Courtoisie]] or [[Il Giornale]], and his writings have been published in several academic journals like the [[New Left]] [[Telos (journal)|''Telos'']], the [[white nationalist]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Measured Lies: The Bell Curve Examined|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-0-312-17228-2|editor1-last=Gresson|editor1-first=Aaron|edition=1st St. Martin's Griffin|page=39|editor2-last=Kincheloe|editor2-first=Joe L.|editor2-link=Joe L. Kincheloe|editor3-last=Steinberg|editor3-first=Shirley R.|editor3-link=Shirley R. Steinberg|title-link=Measured Lies: The Bell Curve Examined}}</ref> ''[[Mankind Quarterly]]'', the [[Paleoconservatism|paleoconservative]] ''[[Chronicles (magazine)|Chronicles]]'', the nationalist ''[[The Occidental Quarterly|Occidental Quarterly]]'' and the [[Traditionalist School|radical traditionalist]] ''[[Tyr (journal)|Tyr]]''.<ref>Fran\u00e7ois, St\u00e9phane. \u00ab The gods looked down : la musique \u00ab industrielle \u00bb et le paganisme \u00bb, ''Soci\u00e9t\u00e9s'', vol. n<sup>o</sup> 88, no. 2, 2005, pp. 109\u2013124. ([https://www.cairn.info/revue-societes-2005-2-page-109.htm Read online])</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unz.com/print/author/DeBenoistAlain/|title=Publication|website=The Unz Review|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was one of the adherents to the 2002 ''[[Manifesto Against the Death of the Spirit and the Earth]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal|issue=44|journal=Bulletin d'Histoire Contemporaine de l'Espagne|location=Aix-en-Provence|publisher=[[Publications de l'Universit\u00e9 de Provence|Publications de l\u2019universit\u00e9 de Provence]]|title=Las \"otras\" derechas en la Espa\u00f1a actual. Te\u00f3logos, \"racionalistas\" y neoderechistas|first=Pedro Carlos|last=Gonz\u00e1lez Cuevas|issn=0987-4135|pages=276\u2013277}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/181/18153296003.pdf|title=Contra la muerte del esp\u00edritu: \u00faltimos avatares de una nouvelle droite a la espa\u00f1ola|journal=N\u00f3madas. Critical Journal of Social and Juridical Sciences|volume=13|issue=1|year=2006|last=Sanrom\u00e1n|first=Diego L.|issn=1578-6730}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2002 republication of ''Vu de droite'', de Benoist reiterated what he wrote in 1977: the \"greatest\" danger in the world today was the \"progressive disappearance of diversity from the world,\" including biodiversity of animals, cultures and peoples.<ref name=\":5\" /> De Benoist is now the editor of two journals: ''Nouvelle \u00c9cole'' (since 1968), and ''Krisis'' (since 1988).<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=phhhHT64kIMC|title=International Who's Who of Authors and Writers 2004|last=Publications|first=Europa|date=2003|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=9781857431797|pages=49|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the extent of the relationship is debated by scholars, de Benoist and the [[Nouvelle Droite]] have influenced the ideological and political structure of the European [[Identitarian movement|Identitarian Movement]].<ref name=\":022\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=UUSCDwAAQBAJ|title=Key Thinkers of the Radical Right: Behind the New Threat to Liberal Democracy|last=Sedgwick|first=Mark|date=8 January 2019|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190877613|pages=73|language=en|quote=Since the early 1990s, the French New Right has been influential beyond France, especially in Italy, Germany, and Belgium, and has inspired Alexander Dugin in Russia. Part of the American radical Right and \"Alt Right\" also claims to have been inspired by de Benoist\u2019s writings. Although this is questionable, de Benoist and Dominique Venner are also seen as the forefathers of the \"identitarian\" movement in Europe.}}</ref><ref name=\"LionsNorth2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=AHmuDQAAQBAJ|title=Lions of the North: Sounds of the New Nordic Radical Nationalism|last=Teitelbaum|first=Benjamin R.|date=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190212599|pages=46|language=en}}</ref> Part of the [[alt-right]] also claims to have been inspired by de Benoist's writings.<ref name=\":022\" />\n\n==Views==\n\nFrom being close to pro-colonial movements and adopting an ethnobiological perspective at the beginning of his writings in the 1960s,<ref>Alain de Benoist: \"What makes a population move towards greater quality is that valuable men, the elites, can in turn procreate and transmit, according to the laws of heredity, their exceptional abilities and gifts.\" (Avec ou sans Dieu ?, 1970, p. 88)</ref><ref name=\":15\" /> when he endorsed [[apartheid]] with Gilles Fournier as the \"last outpost of the West\" at a time of \"decolonisation and international negrification\",<ref name=\":9\" /> de Benoist gradually moved towards a [[Third-Worldism|defense of the Third-World]] against [[American imperialism]] and a more cultural definition of \"difference\", theorized in his concept of [[ethnopluralism]]. De Benoist is also an ardent critic of [[globalisation]], unrestricted [[Immigration|mass immigration]], [[liberalism]], [[Postmodernity|postmodern society]] and what he calls the \"ideology of sameness\".<ref name=\":52\" /><ref name=\":11\" /> Scholars question if this evolution in de Benoist's concepts should be considered a sincere ideological detachment from a far-right activist youth,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liberation.fr/france/2015/03/09/alain-de-benoist-n-a-rien-a-voir-avec-le-fn_1217324|title=Pol\u00e9mique Valls-Onfray : Les n\u00e9odroitiers ont contribu\u00e9 \u00e0 structurer le FN, sans en devenir la matrice|last=Fran\u00e7ois|first=St\u00e9phane|authorlink=St\u00e9phane Fran\u00e7ois|date=9 March 2015|website=[[Lib\u00e9ration]]|language=fr|access-date=18 August 2019}}</ref> or rather a meta-political strategy to reshape unegalitarian ideas into acceptable differentialist terms.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|date=2014|title=A Response to Alain de Benoist|journal=Journal for the Study of Radicalism|volume=8|issue=2|pages=123\u2013168|doi=10.14321/jstudradi.8.2.0123|issn=1930-1189|jstor=10.14321/jstudradi.8.2.0123|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/18859076e17881ddf6b4ab222967648e173eb3f9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taguieff|first=Pierre-Andr\u00e9|author-link=Pierre-Andr\u00e9 Taguieff|date=1993|title=Origines et m\u00e9tamorphoses de la Nouvelle Droite|journal=Vingti\u00e8me Si\u00e8cle. Revue d'histoire|issue=40|pages=3\u201322|doi=10.2307/3770354|issn=0294-1759|jstor=3770354}}</ref>\n\nPolitical scientist [[Jean-Yves Camus]] describes the key idea of de Benoist's writings in those terms: \"through the use of [[Metapolitics|meta-politics]], to think the ways and means that are necessary in order for European civilization, based on the cultural values shared on the continent until the advent of globalization, to thrive and be perpetuated.\"<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=UUSCDwAAQBAJ|title=Key Thinkers of the Radical Right: Behind the New Threat to Liberal Democracy|last=Sedgwick|first=Mark|date=8 January 2019|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190877613|pages=75\u201376|language=en}}</ref> Though he embodies the core values of GRECE and the Nouvelle Droite, de Benoist\u2019s works are not always identical to those of other thinkers of the movements. He for instance disavowed [[Guillaume Faye]]'s \"strongly racist\" ideas regarding Muslims after the publication of ''The Colonization of Europe: Speaking Truth about Immigration and Islam'' in 2000.<ref name=\":12\" /> De Benoist is indeed opposed to political violence, stating that he had been building \"a school of thought, not a political movement.\"<ref>France;Ideas and bombs The Economist 23 August 1980</ref>\n\n=== Identity ===\nInspired by [[Martin Buber]]'s [[philosophy of dialogue]] and his ''[[I and Thou|Ich und Du]]'' concept, de Benoist defined \"identity\" as a \"dialogical\" phenomenon in ''We and the Others'' (\"Nous et les autres\", 2006). According to him, one's identity is made of two components: the \"objective part\" that comes from one\u2019s background (ethnicity, religion, family, nationality), and the \"subjective part\", freely chosen by the individual. Identity is therefore a process in constant evolution, rather than a completely fixed notion.<ref name=\":12\" /> In 1992, he consequently dismissed the [[National Rally (France)|Front National]] use of ethnopluralism, on the grounds that it portrayed \"difference as an absolute, whereas, by definition, it exists only relationally.\"<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=_j5YDgAAQBAJ|title=Far-Right Politics in Europe|last=Camus|first=Jean-Yves|last2=Lebourg|first2=Nicolas|date=20 March 2017|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674971530|pages=124|language=en}}</ref><ref>Sharon Waxman, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-12-13/features/9312130011_1_intellectuals-debate-anti-immigrant \u2033Europe's Left And Right Are Too Divided To Even Talk About It\u2033], Chicago Tribune, 13 December 1993. Retrieved 21 June 2017.</ref> De Benoist believes that knowledge of ethnic and religious traditions is a duty, which must be passed on to following generation, and is critical of the idea of a moral imperative to [[cosmopolitanism]].<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=UUSCDwAAQBAJ|title=Key Thinkers of the Radical Right: Behind the New Threat to Liberal Democracy|last=Sedgwick|first=Mark|date=8 January 2019|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190877613|pages=78|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIf scholars like [[Pierre-Andr\u00e9 Taguieff]] have labeled the [[Nouvelle Droite]] a form of \"mixophobia\", due to its focus on the concept of \"difference\", de Benoist has also criticized what he calls \"the pathology of identity\", that is to say the political use of identity by the [[Right-wing populism|populist Right]] in order to push an \"us versus them\" debate escorted by \"[systematic] and [irrational] hating\". The difficulty of understanding de Benoist\u2019s views on identity lies in the fact that his writings have experienced multiple re-synthesis since the 1960s. In 1974, he said: \"there is no superior race. All races are superior and each of them has its own genius\".<ref name=\":14\" /> Suspicions have arisen of a subtle meta-political guise designed with the aim of re-establishing the original fascist idea around a new framework, and de Benoist has been influenced by [[Carl Schmitt]]'s distinction between friend and enemy as the core issue of politics. He however sees immigrants as eventually victims of [[globalization]], and also explained that immigration was first of all a consequence of big companies being greedy for profits and preferring to import cheap labor.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\n=== Ethnopluralism ===\nDe Benoist rejects the [[nation state]] and [[nationalism]], on the ground that both liberalism and nationalism eventually derive from the same [[metaphysics]] of [[subjectivity]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=UUSCDwAAQBAJ|title=Key Thinkers of the Radical Right: Behind the New Threat to Liberal Democracy|last=Sedgwick|first=Mark|date=8 January 2019|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190877613|pages=76|language=en}}</ref> and that the centralized and \"[[Jacobin]]\" state [[France|French Republic]] had destroyed regional identities in the project of \"one and indivisible\" France.<ref name=\":5\" /> He stands instead for the political autonomy of each and every group, favoring an integral federalism built on the principle of subsidiarity, that would transcend the nation state and give way to regional identities and a common continental one at once.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=De Benoist|first=Alain|date=2014|title=Alain de Benoist Answers Tamir Bar-On|journal=Journal for the Study of Radicalism|volume=8|issue=1|pages=141\u2013168|doi=10.14321/jstudradi.8.1.0141|jstor=10.14321/jstudradi.8.1.0141|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/6407098cda6c7f46f6ae2890aa54f0eff2261409}}</ref>\n\n=== Liberalism ===\nDe Benoist is a critic of the primacy of [[Individual and group rights|individual rights]], an ideology he sees embodied in [[humanism]], the [[French Revolution]], and the [[Founding Fathers of the United States|American Founding Fathers]]. While not a [[Marxism|Marxist]], de Benoist has been influenced by the communist analysis of the nature of capitalism and conflicting class interests, exposed by [[Karl Marx]] in ''Das Kapital.'' As a result, another of his core ideas is that the world is facing the \"hegemony of capital\" and the \"pursuit of self-interest\", two typical trends of the [[Postmodernity|postmodern era]]. According to Jean-Yves Camus however, if de Benoist can share anti-capitalist analysis with leftists, the nature of his goal is indeed different, as de Benoist considers the unlimited expansion of the free market and [[consumerism]] as key contributors to the erasure of peoples' identities. Furthermore, although he aknowledges their existence, he does not makes an essential distinction between the \"[[working class]]\" and the \"[[bourgeoise]]\", but rather between the \"new dominant class\" and the \"people\".<ref name=\":12\" /> In 1991, his magazine ''El\u00e9ments'' described via its editorial staff how \"too systematic anti-egalitarianism [could] lead to [[social Darwinism]], which might justify [[free-market economy]]\".<ref name=\":14\" />\n\n=== United States ===\nDe Benoist is opposed to the [[Liberalism in the United States|American liberal]] idea of a [[melting pot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/EuropeanSonAnInterviewWithAlainDeBenoist|title=European Son : An Interview with Alain de Benoist|format=PDF|accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref> A critic of the [[United States]], he has been quoted as saying: \"Some people do not accept the thought of one day having to wear the Red Army cap. In fact, it is a terrible prospect. However, this is not a reason to tolerate the idea of one day having to spend what we have left to live on by eating hamburgers in Brooklyn.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liberation.fr/france/2016/04/08/la-passion-russe-de-l-extreme-droite_1444969|title=La passion russe de l'extr\u00eame droite|date=8 April 2016|website=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|language=fr|access-date=18 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Orientations pour des ann\u00e9es d\u00e9cisives|last=De Benoist|first=Alain|publisher=Labyrinthe|year=1982|location=Paris|pages=76|quote=Certains ne se r\u00e9signent pas \u00e0 la pens\u00e9e d\u2019avoir un jour \u00e0 porter la casquette de l\u2019Arm\u00e9e rouge. De fait, c\u2019est une perspective affreuse. Nous ne pouvons pas, pour autant, supporter l\u2019id\u00e9e d\u2019avoir un jour \u00e0 passer ce qui nous reste \u00e0 vivre en mangeant des hamburgers du c\u00f4t\u00e9 de Brooklyn.}}</ref> In 1991, he complained that European supporters of the first [[Gulf War]] were \"collaborators of the American order.\"<ref>Rone Tempest, [http://articles.latimes.com/print/1991-02-15/news/mn-1225_1_secret-agenda \"French Revive a Pastime: Fretting About U.S. 'Imperialism' : Reaction: Talk of 'secret agendas' surfaces on the left and the right. Some chafe at their country's secondary role in the Gulf. Others worry about diminished European influence,\"] ''Los Angeles Times'', 15 February 1991.</ref>\n\n=== Islam ===\nDe Benoist has supported ties with [[Islamic culture]] in the 1980s,<ref>Under cover story The Guardian (London) 14 August 1987.</ref> on the grounds that the relationship would be distinct from what he saw as the consumerism and materialism of American society, as well as the bureaucracy and repression of the [[Soviet Union]].<ref>The disharmonic convergence: the far left and the far right as strange bedfellows,s Whole Earth Review 22 June 1988</ref>\n\n=== Paganism and Christianity ===\nHe also opposes [[Christianity]] as inherently intolerant, theocratic and bent on persecution.<ref>Intolerance, American-Style;Given This Country's History of Religious Animosities, Thomas Fleming Writes Pittsburgh Post-Gazette (Pennsylvania) 21 December 1997</ref>\n\n== Influences ==\nDe Benoist's influences include [[Antonio Gramsci]],<ref>\u2033The Marcuse factor\u2033, Modern Age, 22 March 2005.</ref> [[Ernst J\u00fcnger]], [[Martin Buber]], [[Jean Baudrillard]], [[Georges Dum\u00e9zil]], [[Ernest Renan]], [[Jos\u00e9 Ortega y Gasset]], [[Vilfredo Pareto]], [[Karl Marx]],<ref name=\":12\" /> [[Guy Debord]], [[Arnold Gehlen]], [[St\u00e9phane Lupasco]], [[Helmut Schelsky]], [[Konrad Lorenz]], the [[Conservative Revolution]]aries, the [[non-conformists of the 1930s]],<ref>\u2033Posthistoire: Has History Come to an End?\u2033, CLIO, 1 January 1994.</ref> [[Johann Gottfried Herder]], [[Johannes Althusius]], interwar [[Austromarxism|Austro-Marxists]],<ref name=\":12\" /> and [[communitarian]] philosophers such as [[Alasdair MacIntyre]] and [[Charles Taylor (philosopher)|Charles Taylor]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Communitarian Third Way: Alexandre Marc and Ordre Nouveau, 1930\u20132000|last1=Hellman|first1=John|date=2002|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press|page=196}}</ref>\n\n==Critics==\n\nHis critics, such as [[Thomas Sheehan (academic)|Thomas Sheehan]], argue that de Benoist has developed a novel restatement of [[fascism]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sheehan |first=Thomas |title=Myth and Violence: The Fascism of Julius Evola and Alain de Benoist |journal=[[Social Research]]| volume=48 |issue=1 |date=Spring 1981 |pages=45\u201373 | quote= Pages 66\u201367: To summarize: De Benoist's fascism is at odds with Evola's metaphysics but agrees with his social and political philosophy.... [F]or de Benoist, the organic State is an ideal that men can set for themselves and perhaps, with force, establish.}}</ref> [[Roger Griffin]], using an [[ideal type]] definition of fascism which includes \"populist ultra-nationalism\" and \"[[palingenesis]]\" (heroic rebirth), argues that the [[Nouvelle Droite]] draws on such fascist ideologues as [[Armin Mohler]] in a way that allows Nouvelle Droite ideologues such as de Benoist to claim a \"metapolitical\" stance, but which nonetheless has residual fascist ideological elements.<ref name=\"Griffin\">{{cite journal|author=Griffin, Roger|year=2000|title=Between metapolitics and apoliteia: the Nouvelle Droite's strategy for conserving the fascist vision in the 'interregnum'|journal=Modern & Contemporary France|volume=8|issue=1|pages= 35\u201353|doi=10.1080/096394800113349}}</ref> De Benoist's critics also claim his views recall [[Nazism|Nazi]] attempts to replace German Christianity with its own paganism.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Marx, Moses, and the Pagans in the Secular City|last=Sunic|first=Tomislav|journal=CLIO|volume=24|issue=2|date=Winter 1995|pages=169\u2013188|quote=In the age that is heavily laced with the Biblical message, many modern pagan thinkers, for their criticism of biblical monotheism, have been attacked and stigmatized either as unrepentant atheists or as spiritual standard-bearers of fascism. Particularly Nietzsche, Heidegger, and more recently Alain de Benoist came under attack for allegedly espousing the philosophy which, for their contemporary detractors, recalled the earlier national socialist attempts to \"dechristianize\" and \"repaganize\" Germany. <sup>See notably the works by Alfred Rosenberg, ''Der Mythus des 20. Jahrhunderts''(M\u00fcnchen: Hoheneichen Verlag, 1933). Also worth noting is the name of Wilhelm Hauer, ''Deutscher Gottschau'' (Stuttgart: Karl Gutbrod, 1934), who significantly popularized Indo-European mythology among national socialists: on pages 240\u201354 Hauer discusses the difference between Judeo-Christian Semitic beliefs and European paganism.</sup>}}</ref> They note that de Benoist's rejection of the French Revolution's legacy and the allegedly \"abstract\" Rights of Man ties him to the same [[Counter-Enlightenment]] right-wing tradition as counter-revolutionary [[Legitimists]], fascists, [[Vichy France|Vichyites]] and integral nationalists.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Backes |first1=Uwe |last2=Moreau |first2=Patrick |title=The Extreme Right in Europe: Current Trends and Perspectives |date=2011 |publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht |page=335}}</ref>\n\n== Private life ==\nA [[Modern Paganism|neo-pagan]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=de Halleux|first=Andr\u00e9|date=1992|title=D\u00e9m\u00e8tre Th\u00e9raios (\u00e9d.), Quelle religion pour l'Europe ? Un d\u00e9bat sur l'identit\u00e9 religieuse des peuples europ\u00e9ens. 1990|url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/thlou_0080-2654_1992_num_23_2_2562_t1_0255_0000_2|journal=Revue Th\u00e9ologique de Louvain|volume=23|issue=2|pages=255\u2013256}}</ref> de Benoist married Doris Christians in 1971 and has two children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whoswho.fr/bio/alain-de-benoist_11216|title=Alain de Benoist \u2013 Who's Who|website=www.whoswho.fr|language=fr|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> He is a member of the [[high IQ society]] [[Mensa International|Mensa]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://phdn.org/negation/taguieff-heritage-nazi-1981.html|title=Pierre-Andr\u00e9 Taguieff, L'H\u00e9ritage nazi. Des Nouvelles Droites europ\u00e9ennes \u00e0 la litt\u00e9rature niant le g\u00e9nocide|website=phdn.org|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> and owns the largest private library in France,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.franceculture.fr/emissions/le-tete-tete/alain-de-benoist|title=Alain de Benoist|website=France Culture|language=fr|access-date=31 July 2019|quote=Il a la plus grande biblioth\u00e8que priv\u00e9e de France qui compte plus de cent cinquante mille ouvrages.}}</ref> with an estimate of 150,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.causeur.fr/alain-de-benoist-un-intellectuel-aux-antipodes-17355|title=Alain de Benoist : un intellectuel aux antipodes|last=Causeur.fr|last2=Boughezala|first2=Daoud|date=6 May 2012|website=Causeur|language=fr-FR|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> to 250,000 books.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\n==Selected works==\n\n===French===\n\n* ''Salan devant l'opinion'' (sous le pseudonyme de Fabrice Laroche) (Saint-Just, 1963).\n* ''Les Indo-Europ\u00e9ens'' (G.E.D., 1966).\n* ''L'Empirisme logique et la Philosophie du Cercle de Vienne'' (Nouvelle \u00c9cole, 1970).\n* ''[[Friedrich Nietzsche|Nietzsche]]: Morale et \u00ab Grande Politique \u00bb'' (GRECE, 1973).\n* ''[[Konrad Lorenz]] et l'\u00c9thologie moderne'' (Nouvelle \u00c9cole, 1975).\n* ''Vu de droite. Anthologie critique des id\u00e9es contemporaines'' (Copernic, 1977). ([[Prix de l'essai|grand prix de l'essai de l'Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]] 1978)\n* ''Les Bretons'' (Les Cahiers de ''la Bretagne r\u00e9elle'', n\u00b0396 ''bis'', 1978).\n* ''Les Id\u00e9es \u00e0 l'endroit'' (Libres-[[Jean-Edern Hallier|Hallier]], 1978).\n* ''Le Guide pratique des pr\u00e9noms'' (\u00ab Robert de Herte \u00bb et {{sic}} Alain de Benoist), coll. \u00ab Hors-s\u00e9rie d'\"Enfants-Magazine\" \u00bb (Publications Groupe M\u00e9dia, 1979).\n* ''Comment peut-on \u00eatre pa\u00efen ?'' (Albin Michel, 1981).\n* ''Les Traditions d'Europe'' (Paris: Labyrinthe, 1982).\n* ''Orientations pour des ann\u00e9es d\u00e9cisives'' (Labyrinthe, 1982).\n* ''F\u00eater No\u00ebl. L\u00e9gendes et Traditions'' (Atlas-Edena, 1982).\n* ''D\u00e9mocratie : le probl\u00e8me'' (Labyrinthe, 1985)\n* (in collaboration with Andre B\u00e9jin & Julien Freund) ''Racismes, Antiracismes'' (Paris: Librairie des M\u00e9ridiens, 1986)\n* (with Thomas Molnar) ''L'\u00e9clipse du sacr\u00e9: discours et r\u00e9sponses'' (Paris: Table ronde, 1986)\n* ''Europe, Tiers monde, m\u00eame combat'' ([[\u00c9ditions Robert Laffont|Robert Laffont]], 1986).\n* ''Le Grain de sable. Jalons pour une fin de si\u00e8cle'' (Labyrinthe, 1994).\n* ''Nationalisme : Ph\u00e9nom\u00e9nologie et Critique'' (GRECE, 1994).\n* ''D\u00e9mocratie repr\u00e9sentative et D\u00e9mocratie participative'' (GRECE, 1994).\n* ''Nietzsche et la R\u00e9volution conservatrice'' (GRECE, 1994).\n* ''L'Empire int\u00e9rieur'' (Fata Morgana, 1995).\n* ''La Ligne de mire. Discours aux citoyens europ\u00e9ens, t. 1 : 1972\u20131987'' (Labyrinthe, 1995).\n* ''Famille et Soci\u00e9t\u00e9. Origine, Histoire, Actualit\u00e9'' (Labyrinthe, 1996).\n* ''La Ligne de mire. Discours aux citoyens europ\u00e9ens, t. 2 : 1988\u20131995'' (Labyrinthe, 1996).\n* ''[[Louis-Ferdinand C\u00e9line|C\u00e9line]] et l'Allemagne, 1933\u20131945. Une mise au point'' (Le Bulletin c\u00e9linien, 1996).\n* ''Horizon 2000. Trois entretiens avec Alain de Benoist'' (GRECE, 1996).\n* ''La L\u00e9gende de [[Clovis I|Clovis]]'' (Cercle Ernest Renan, 1996).\n* ''Indo-Europ\u00e9ens : \u00e0 la recherche du foyer d'origine'' (Nouvelle \u00c9cole, 1997).\n* ''[[Ernst J\u00fcnger]]. Une bio-bibliographie'' (Guy Tr\u00e9daniel, 1997).\n* ''Communisme et Nazisme. 25 r\u00e9flexions sur le totalitarisme au XXe si\u00e8cle'' (Labyrinthe, 1998).\n* ''L'\u00c9cume et les Galets. 1991\u20131999 : dix ans d'actualit\u00e9 vue d'ailleurs'' (Labyrinthe, 2000).\n* ''J\u00e9sus sous l'\u0153il critique des historiens'' (Cercle Ernest Renan, 2000).\n* ''Bibliographie d'Henri B\u00e9raud'' (Association r\u00e9taise des Amis d'Henri B\u00e9raud, 2000).\n* ''Derni\u00e8re Ann\u00e9e. Notes pour conclure le si\u00e8cle'' (L'\u00c2ge d'Homme, 2001).\n* ''[[J\u00e9sus]] et ses Fr\u00e8res'' (Cercle Ernest Renan, 2001).\n* ''Louis Rougier. Sa vie, son \u0153uvre'' (Cercle Ernest Renan, 2002).\n* ''[[Charles Maurras]] et [[l'Action fran\u00e7aise]]. Une bibliographie'', BCM, 2002\n* ''Qu'est-ce qu'un militant ?'' (sous le pseudonyme de Fabrice Laroche, r\u00e9\u00e9dition d'un article paru en 1963) (Ars Magna, 2003).\n* ''Critiques-Th\u00e9oriques'' (L'\u00c2ge d'Homme, 2003).\n* ''Au-del\u00e0 des droits de l'homme. Pour d\u00e9fendre les libert\u00e9s'' (\u00e9ditions Krisis, 2004).\n* ''Bibliographie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale des droites fran\u00e7aises. 1, [[Arthur de Gobineau]], [[Gustave Le Bon]], [[\u00c9douard Drumont]], [[Maurice Barr\u00e8s]], [[Pierre Drieu La Rochelle]], [[Henry de Montherlant]], [[Thierry Maulnier]], [[Julien Freund]]'' (\u00c9ditions Dualpha, coll. \u00ab Patrimoine des lettres \u00bb, Coulommiers, 2004), 609 p.\n* ''Bibliographie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale des droites fran\u00e7aises. 2, [[Georges Sorel]], [[Charles Maurras]], [[Georges Valois]], [[Abel Bonnard]], [[Henri B\u00e9raud]], [[Louis Rougier]], [[Lucien Rebatet]], [[Robert Brasillach]]'' (\u00c9ditions Dualpha, coll. \u00ab Patrimoine des lettres \u00bb, Coulommiers, 2004), 472 p.\n* ''Bibliographie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale des droites fran\u00e7aises. 3, [[Louis de Bonald]], [[Alexis de Tocqueville]], [[Georges Vacher de Lapouge]], [[L\u00e9on Daudet]], [[Jacques Bainville]], [[Ren\u00e9 Benjamin]], [[Henri Massis]], [[Georges Bernanos]], [[Maurice Bard\u00e8che]], [[Jean Cau (writer)|Jean Cau]]'' (\u00c9ditions Dualpha, coll. \u00ab Patrimoine des lettres \u00bb, Coulommiers, 2005), 648 p.\n* ''Bibliographie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale des droites fran\u00e7aises. 4, [[Joseph de Maistre]], [[Ernest Renan]], [[:fr:Jules Soury|Jules Soury]], [[Charles P\u00e9guy]], [[Alphonse de Chateaubriant]], [[Jacques Benoist-M\u00e9chin]], [[Gustave Thibon]], Saint-Loup ([[Marc Augier]]), [[Louis Pauwels]]'' (\u00c9ditions Dualpha, coll. \u00ab Patrimoine des lettres \u00bb, Coulommiers, 2005), 736 p.\n* ''J\u00e9sus et ses Fr\u00e8res, et autres \u00e9crits sur le christianisme, le paganisme et la religion'' (\u00e9ditions Les Amis d'Alain de Benoist, 2006).\n* ''C'est-\u00e0-dire. Entretiens-T\u00e9moignages-Explications'' (2 volumes) (\u00e9ditions Les Amis d'Alain de Benoist, 2006).\n* ''Nous et les autres. Probl\u00e9matique de l'identit\u00e9'' (\u00e9ditions Krisis, 2006).\n* ''[[Carl Schmitt]] actuel'' (\u00e9ditions Krisis, 2007).\n* ''Demain, la d\u00e9croissance ! Penser l'\u00e9cologie jusqu'au bout'' (Edite, 2007).\n* [http://www.revue-elements.com/livres-Textes-Politiques-1919-1945.html ''Dictionnaire des pr\u00e9noms : d'hier et d'aujourd'hui, d'ici et d'ailleurs''] (Jean Picollec, 2009).\n* ''M\u00e9moire vive / Entretiens avec Fran\u00e7ois Bousquet'' (\u00c9ditions de Fallois, Collection \u00ab Litt\u00e9rature \u00bb, 2 mai 2012).\n* ''Edouard Berth ou le socialisme h\u00e9ro\u00efque. Sorel, Maurras, Lenine'' (Pard\u00e8s, 2013).\n* ''Les D\u00e9mons du Bien, Du nouvel ordre moral \u00e0 l'id\u00e9ologie du genre'' (Pierre-Guillaume de Roux, 2013).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* ''[[Fascism (book)|Fascism]]'', edited by [[Roger Griffin]] (1995), pp.&nbsp;346\u2013348.\n* ''[[The Beast Reawakens]]'' by [[Martin A. Lee]] (1997), pp.&nbsp;208\u2013213.\n* ''[[Biographical Dictionary of the Extreme Right Since 1890]]'' (1990), edited by [[Philip Rees]], pp.&nbsp;29\u201330.\n\n==Further reading==\n* Jonathan Marcus, ''The National Front and French Politics'', New York: New York University Press, 1995, pp.&nbsp;22\u20134, 151.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official}}\n\n{{Alt-right footer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benoist, Alain de}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alt-right]]\n[[Category:Alt-right writers]]\n[[Category:People from Tours, France]]\n[[Category:French political philosophers]]\n[[Category:New Right (Europe)]]\n[[Category:Geopoliticians]]\n[[Category:French political writers]]\n[[Category:French neopagans]]\n[[Category:Identitarian movement in France]]\n[[Category:20th-century French philosophers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:French male essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century French essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century French essayists]]\n[[Category:Critics of Christianity]]\n[[Category:Anti-consumerists]]\n[[Category:Degrowth advocates]]\n[[Category:Prix de l'essai laureates]]\n[[Category:20th-century French male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century French male writers]]\n[[Category:Neopagan writers]]\n[[Category:Pan-European nationalism]]\n[[Category:Neopaganism in France]]\n[[Category:Indo-Europeanists]]\n[[Category:French nationalists]]\n[[Category:Runologists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French journalist and political theorist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox philosopher\n| image         = 20110402 De Benoist.png\n| caption       = Alain de Benoist in 2012\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1943|12|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Tours]], [[Indre-et-Loire]], [[France]]\n| alias         = Fabrice Laroche, Robert de Herte, David Barney\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Paris]]\n| occupation    = Journalist, essayist \n| relatives     = [[Gustave Moreau]] (great-granduncle)<ref>Michael B\u00f6hm, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Ty_MBj109EQC&dq= ''Alain de Benoist und die Nouvelle Droite''], LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster, 2008, p. 47.</ref>\n| years_active  = 1960\u2013present\n| school_tradition = ''[[Nouvelle Droite]]''\n| notable_ideas= Modernization and secularization of Christian Values, Repaganization of the West, [[Pens\u00e9e unique]], [[Nouvelle Droite]], [[Ethnopluralism]]\n| influences    = [[Johann Gottfried Herder|Herder]], [[Carl Schmitt|Schmitt]], [[Antonio Gramsci|Gramsci]], [[Julius Evola|Evola]], [[Friedrich Nietzsche|Nietzsche]], [[Louis Dumont|Dumont]], [[Martin Heidegger|Heidegger]], [[Jean Baudrillard|Baudrillard]], [[Oswald Spengler|Spengler]], [[Ernst J\u00fcnger|J\u00fcnger]], [[Giorgio Locchi|Locchi]], [[Georges Dum\u00e9zil|Dum\u00e9zil]], [[Jos\u00e9 Ortega y Gasset|Ortega y Gasset]], [[Vilfredo Pareto|Pareto]], [[Alasdair MacIntyre|MacIntyre]], [[Charles Taylor (philosopher)|Taylor]], [[Martin Buber|Buber]], [[Karl Marx|Marx]]\n| influenced    = [[Guillaume Faye]], [[Marco Tarchi]], [[Patrice de Plunkett]], [[Dragoslav Bokan]], [[Martin A. Lee]], [[Pat Buchanan]], [[Aleksandr Dugin]]\n}}\n\n'''Alain de Benoist de Gentissart''' ({{IPAc-en|d|\u0259|_|b|\u0259|\u02c8|n|w|\u0251\u02d0}}; {{IPA-fr|d\u0259 b\u0259nwa|lang}}; born 11 December 1943), also known as Fabrice Laroche, Robert de Herte and other aliases,<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=UUSCDwAAQBAJ|title=Key Thinkers of the Radical Right: Behind the New Threat to Liberal Democracy|last=Sedgwick|first=Mark|date=8 January 2019|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190877613|pages=74\u201375|language=en}}</ref> is a [[French people|French]] journalist and political philosopher, a founding member of the [[Nouvelle Droite]] (\"New Right\"), and the leader of the [[Ethnic nationalism|ethno-nationalist]] think tank [[Groupement de recherche et d'\u00e9tudes pour la civilisation europ\u00e9enne|GRECE]].\n\nPrincipally influenced by thinkers of the [[Conservative Revolution|German Conservative Revolution]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=N5KoDQAAQBAJ|title=Where Have All The Fascists Gone?|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|date=5 December 2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351873130|pages=340|language=en}}</ref> de Benoist is opposed to [[Christianity]], the [[Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen|rights of man]], [[neoliberalism]], [[representative democracy]], [[egalitarianism]]; and what he sees as embodying and promoting those values, namely the [[United States]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|title=Intellectual Right \u2013 Wing Extremism \u2013 Alain de Benoist's Mazeway Resynthesis since 2000|date=7 December 2011|work=The Extreme Right in Europe|pages=335|editor-last=Backes|editor-first=Uwe|edition=1|publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht|language=en|doi=10.13109/9783666369223.333|isbn=9783525369227|quote=De Benoist\u2019s continued anti-egalitarianism, rejection of the Rights of Man and representative democracy, as well as valorization of pagan elite rule [...]|editor2-last=Moreau|editor2-first=Patrick|chapter=Intellectual Right - Wing Extremism \u2013 Alain de Benoist's Mazeway Resynthesis since 2000}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Trouble on the right; recent gains by the extreme-right leader Jean-Marie Le Pen have left conservatives and moderates confused about whether to imitate or attack him; France The Atlantic February 1985</ref><ref>{{cite book|quote=In contrast, on this side of the Atlantic, a liberal is primarily a spokesman of individualism, a supporter of free trade, and an opponent of the state (and also a supporter of America).|first=Alain|last=de Benoist|chapter=Preface: The New Right: Forty Years After|editor-first=Tomislav|editor-last=Sunic|title=Against Democracy and Equality|isbn=978-1-907166-25-9|year=2011}}</ref> He theorized the notion of [[ethnopluralism]], a concept which relies on preserving and mutually respecting individual and bordered ethno-cultural regions.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|date=2001|title=The Ambiguities of the Nouvelle Droite, 1968\u20131999|journal=The European Legacy|volume=6|issue=3|pages=333\u2013351|doi=10.1080/10848770120051349|via=Taylor & Francis}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=McCulloch|first=Tom|date=1 August 2006|title=The Nouvelle Droite in the 1980s and 1990s: Ideology and Entryism, the Relationship with the Front National|journal=French Politics|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=158\u2013178|doi=10.1057/palgrave.fp.8200099|issn=1476-3419|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/2ed0f6b2f7b333ba7ff36154bfb9e394f49b0229}}</ref>\n\nHis work has been influential with the [[alt-right]] movement in the United States, and he presented a lecture on identity at a [[National Policy Institute]] conference hosted by [[Richard B. Spencer]]; however, he has distanced himself from the movement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/the-french-ideologues-who-inspired-the-alt-right|title=The French Ideologues Who Inspired the Alt-Right|last=Kennedy|first=Dana|date=30 January 2017|newspaper=The Daily Beast|access-date=22 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mohdin |first1=Aamna |title=The alt-right are targeting disgruntled white male lefties to join their movement |url=https://qz.com/1176355/how-richard-spencer-and-the-alt-right-are-adopting-left-wing-language-to-recruit-leftie-men/ |accessdate=23 August 2018 |work=Quartz |date=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n=== Early life (1943\u20131961) ===\n[[File:Blason famille fr Benoist.svg|thumb|[[Coat of arms]] of House de Benoist]]\nAlain de Benoist de Gentissart<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=_JNaHlYENu8C|title=Extr\u00e9mismes. enqu\u00eate sur une grande peur contemporaine|last=Bourseiller|first=Christophe|date=15 January 2012|publisher=CNRS|isbn=9782271073624|language=fr}}</ref> was born on 11 December 1943 in Saint-Symphorien (now part of [[Tours]]), [[Centre-Val de Loire]],<ref name=\":5\">{{Citation|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|title=Intellectual Right - Wing Extremism \u2013 Alain de Benoist's Mazeway Resynthesis since 2000|date=7 December 2011|work=The Extreme Right in Europe|pages=333\u2013340|editor-last=Backes|editor-first=Uwe|edition=1|publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht|language=en|doi=10.13109/9783666369223.333|isbn=9783525369227|editor2-last=Moreau|editor2-first=Patrick}}</ref> the son of a head of sales at [[Guerlain]], also named Alain de Benoist (1902\u20131971), and Germaine Langou\u00ebt (1908\u20131981).<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> De Benoist grew up in a bourgeois and [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] family.<ref name=\":7\" /> While his mother came from the lower-middle class of [[Normandy]] and [[Brittany]], his father allegedly belonged to the Belgian nobility.<ref name=\":11\" /> During [[World War II|WWII]], de Benoist's father was a member of the [[French resistance|resistance]] armed group [[French Forces of the Interior]]. He was a self-declared [[Gaullism|Gaullist]], while his wife Germaine was rather left-leaning;<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=t-lMZhdWxGoC|title=L'Europe en chemise noire: Les extr\u00eames droites europ\u00e9ennes de 1945 \u00e0 aujourd'hui|last=Milza|first=Pierre|date=4 September 2002|publisher=Fayard|isbn=9782213651064|language=fr}}</ref> and the de Benoist family divided between [[Free France]] and [[Vichy France]] during the war.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=OW_7pvGOxKUC|title=La Guerre d'Alg\u00e9rie et les intellectuels fran\u00e7ais|last=Rioux|first=Jean-Pierre|last2=Sirinelli|first2=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|date=1991|publisher=Editions Complexe|isbn=9782870273777|pages=61|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nDe Benoist was still in high school at [[Lyc\u00e9e Montaigne (Paris)|Lyc\u00e9e Montaigne]] and [[Lyc\u00e9e Louis-le-Grand|Louis-le-Grand]] during the turmoils of the [[Algerian War|Algerian war]] (1954-1962),<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=V3toDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT23|title=Les plastiqueurs: Une histoire secr\u00e8te de l'extr\u00eame droite violente|last=Charpier|first=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|date=23 August 2018|publisher=La D\u00e9couverte|isbn=9782348035579|pages=23|language=fr}}</ref> a moment that shaped his political views.<ref name=\":11\" /> In 1957 at 14, he met the daughter of the [[Antisemitism|antisemite]] journalist and [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theorist]] [[Henry Coston]], and began his journalist career three years later by writing for Henry Coston's magazine, ''Lectures Fran\u00e7aises.<ref name=\":7\" />''<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=938sDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA78|title=Hate: The Rising Tide of Anti-Semitism in France (and What It Means for Us)|last=Weitzmann|first=Marc|date=12 March 2019|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|isbn=9780544791343|pages=77\u201378|language=en}}</ref> De Benoist however stayed away from Coston\u2019s conspiracy theories on the [[Freemasonry]] and the Jews.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nAt 17 in 1961, he met [[Fran\u00e7ois d'Orcival]], with whom he became the editor of an underground newspaper for the pro-colonial paramilitary organisation [[Organisation arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te|OAS]], titled ''France Information''.<ref name=\":2\">Philippe Lamy (under the dir. of Claude Dargent), ''Le Club de l\u2019horloge (1974\u20132002): \u00e9volution et mutation d\u2019un laboratoire id\u00e9ologique'', Paris, universit\u00e9 Paris-VIII, 2016. p. 86, 97, 99 ([http://www.theses.fr/2016PA080034/document read online])</ref> The same year, he joined the student society [[Federation of Nationalist Students]] (FEN) and became in 1962 the secretary of the organization's magazine, ''Cahiers universitaires'', in which he wrote the main articles along with D'Orcival.''<ref name=\":7\" />''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=frhYDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT30|title=Vous avez dit fascismes ?|last=Taguieff|first=Pierre-Andr\u00e9|last2=Tarnero|first2=Jacques|last3=Badinter|first3=Robert|date=31 December 1983|publisher=FeniXX r\u00e9\u00e9dition num\u00e9rique|isbn=9782402119221|pages=30\u201333|language=fr}}</ref> As a student in law and literature, he began a period of political activism and passion for [[Fantastique|fantastique cinema]].<ref name=\":16\" /> According to [[Pierre-Andr\u00e9 Taguieff]] and [[Pierre Milza]], de Benoist had an intellectual curiosity that was lacking from his elder colleagues [[Dominique Venner]] (1935\u20132013) and [[Jean Mabire]] (1927\u20132006), and the young journalist led them to discover a conceptual universe \"that they could not imagine\", no more than its \"possible ideological exploitations\".<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Radical political activism (1962\u20131967) ===\nDe Benoist met [[Dominique Venner]] in 1962.''<ref name=\":7\" />'' The following year, he took part in the creation of ''[[Europe-Action]]'', a [[white nationalist]] magazine created by Venner in which he worked as a journalist.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=OW_7pvGOxKUC|title=La Guerre d'Alg\u00e9rie et les intellectuels fran\u00e7ais|last=Rioux|first=Jean-Pierre|last2=Sirinelli|first2=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|date=1991|publisher=Editions Complexe|isbn=9782870273777|pages=65\u201366|language=fr}}</ref> De Benoist published at that times his first essays: ''[[Raoul Salan|Salan]] devant l'opinion'' (\"Salan faces the (public) opinion\", 1963) and ''Le courage est leur patrie'' (\"Braveness is their motherland\", 1965), defending [[French Algeria]] and the [[Organisation arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te|OAS]].''<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":17\" />''\n\nBetween 1963 and 1965, de Benoist was a member of the [[Rationalist Union]] and likely began to read [[Louis Rougier]]'s [[criticism of Christianity]]\u2014who was also an adherent of the organization\u2014during this period. They maintained a relationship and Rougier's thesis deeply influenced de Benoist's own [[Criticism of Christianity|anti-Christianity]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=D1WwAAAAIAAJ|title=Sur la Nouvelle Droite: jalons d'une analyse critique|last=Taguieff|first=Pierre Andr\u00e9|date=1994|publisher=Descartes et Cie|isbn=9782910301026|pages=137|language=fr}}</ref> \"We oppose Rougier to [[Jean-Paul Sartre|Sartre]],\" de Benoist wrote in 1965, \"like we oppose verbal delirium to logics [...], because biologicial realism is the best support against those idealistic chimeras\".<ref name=\":7\" /> De Benoist continued his journalistic career and became in 1964 the editor-in-chief of the weekly publication ''[[Europe-Action]] Hebdomaire'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=g1JPDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT201|title=The French National Front: The Extremist Challenge To Democracy|last=Simmons|first=Harvey G.|date=5 March 2018|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780429976179|pages=201|language=en}}</ref> holding the same position at ''L'Observateur Europ\u00e9en'' from 1964 to 1968''.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Taguieff|first=Pierre-Andr\u00e9|date=1993|title=Origines et m\u00e9tamorphoses de la Nouvelle Droite|journal=Vingti\u00e8me Si\u00e8cle. Revue d'histoire|issue=40|pages=5\u20136|doi=10.2307/3770354|issn=0294-1759|jstor=3770354}}</ref>'' He also wrote in the [[neo-fascist]] magazine ''[[D\u00e9fense de l\u2019Occident|D\u00e9fense de l'Occident]]'', founded in 1952 by [[Maurice Bard\u00e8che]].<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nAfter a visit to [[South Africa]] at the invitation of [[Hendrik Verwoerd]]'s [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] government, de Benoist co-wrote with Gilles Fournier the 1965 essay ''V\u00e9rit\u00e9 pour l'Afrique du Sud'' (\"Truth for South Africa\"), in which they endorsed [[apartheid]].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=7eGJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA121|title=The Extreme Right in France: From P\u00e9tain to Le Pen|last=Shields|first=James|date=7 May 2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134861118|pages=121|language=en}}</ref> The following year, he co-wrote with D'Orcival another essay, ''Rhod\u00e9sie, pays des lions fid\u00e8les'' (\"Rhodesia, country of the faithful lions\", 1966), in defense of [[Rhodesia]], a breakaway country in southern Africa ruled by a white-minority government. The then prime minister of the [[List of historical unrecognized states and dependencies|unrecognised state]], [[Ian Smith]], prefaced the book.<ref name=\":10\" /> Returning from a trip to the [[United States]], de Benoist deplored the suppression of [[Racial segregation in the United States|racial segregation]] and wrote as a prediction that the system would survive outside the law, thus in a more violent way.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>Alain de Benoist: \"The legal segregation removed (and it will be removed everywhere, we must not be under any illusions) is immediately replaced by a ''de facto'' segregation over which the legal, and therefore peaceful, means have no more influence.\" (''Europe-Action'', octobre 1965 (34), <abbr>pp.</abbr> 9\u201312)</ref>\n\nIn two essays published in 1966, ''Les Indo-Europ\u00e9ens'' (\"The [[Proto-Indo-Europeans|Indo-Europeans]]\") and ''Qu'est-ce que le nationalisme?'' (\"What is nationalism?\"), de Benoist contributed to define a new [[Pan-European nationalism|European nationalism]], where the European civilization\u2014or the \"white race\"\u2014<ref name=\":15\">Alain de Benoist: \"Race is the only real unit encompassing individual variations. The objective study of history shows that only the European race (white race, caucasian) has continued to progress since its appearance on the rising path of the evolution of the living, unlike races stagnant in their development, therefore in virtual regression [...] The European race does not have absolute superiority. It is only the most capable of progressing in the direction of evolution [...] Racial factors being statistically hereditary, each race has its own psychology. All psychology generates value.\" (Qu'est-ce que le nationalisme?, 1966, pp. 8\u20139)</ref> would be considered above its constituting ethnic groups, all united in a common empire and civilization including [[Russia]]. This theory was embodied in the program of the [[European Rally for Liberty]] (REL), in which de Benoist was a member of the national council, during the [[1967 French legislative election|1967 legislative election]], and later became a core idea of GRECE in 1968.<ref name=\":82\">{{Cite journal|last=Taguieff|first=Pierre-Andr\u00e9|date=1993|title=Origines et m\u00e9tamorphoses de la Nouvelle Droite|journal=Vingti\u00e8me Si\u00e8cle. Revue d'histoire|issue=40|pages=4\u20136|doi=10.2307/3770354|issn=0294-1759|jstor=3770354}}</ref>\n\nThe successive electoral failures of far-right movements\u2014from that of presidential candidate [[Jean-Louis Tixier-Vignancour]] in 1965, who de Benoist had supported via the \"T.V. Committees\", to the debacle of the REL in March 1967,\u2014led de Benoist to question his political involvement and focus on a [[Metapolitics|meta-political]] strategy. In the fall of 1967, he decided to make a \"permanent and complete break with political action\" and to launch a review.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=_j5YDgAAQBAJ|title=Far-Right Politics in Europe|last=Camus|first=Jean-Yves|last2=Lebourg|first2=Nicolas|date=20 March 2017|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674971530|pages=132\u201333|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":82\" /> During the [[May 1968 events in France|May 1968 events]], then 25, he was a journalist for the [[professional magazine]] ''L'\u00c9cho de la presse et de la publicit\u00e9''.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\n=== Nouvelle Droite and media fame (1968\u20131993) ===\nAlong with militants of the REL and FEN, de Benoist founded in 1968 GRECE, an [[Ethnic nationalism|ethnonationalist]] [[think-tank]], of which he soon became the leader and its \"most authoritative spokesman\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Spektorowski|first=Alberto|date=1 February 2003|title=The New Right: Ethno-regionalism, ethno-pluralism and the emergence of a neo-fascist 'Third Way'|journal=Journal of Political Ideologies|volume=8|issue=1|pages=116|doi=10.1080/13569310306084|issn=1356-9317}}</ref><ref>Griffin, Roger (2000). \"Between Metapolitics and Apoliteia: the Nouvelle Droite's Strategy for Conserving the Fascist Vision in the 'Interregnum'\". Modern & Contemporary France. 8 (1): p. 35</ref> In the 1970s, de Benoist adapted his geopolitical view-points, from a pro-colonial attitude towards [[third-Worldism]];<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=OW_7pvGOxKUC|title=La Guerre d'Alg\u00e9rie et les intellectuels fran\u00e7ais|last=Rioux|first=Jean-Pierre|last2=Sirinelli|first2=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|date=1991|publisher=Editions Complexe|isbn=9782870273777|pages=76|language=fr}}</ref> from the defense of the \"last outposts of the West\" towards [[Anti-Americanism|anti-americanism]];<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=D1WwAAAAIAAJ|title=Sur la Nouvelle Droite: jalons d'une analyse critique|last=Taguieff|first=Pierre Andr\u00e9|date=1994|publisher=Descartes et Cie|isbn=9782910301026|pages=300|language=fr}}</ref> and from a biological to a cultural definition of \"difference\", developed in his [[Ethnopluralism|ethnopluralist]] theories.<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite journal|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|date=1 June 2001|title=The Ambiguities of the Nouvelle Droite, 1968\u20131999|journal=The European Legacy|volume=6|issue=3|pages=339|doi=10.1080/10848770120051349|issn=1084-8770}}</ref>\n\nHis works, along with others published by the think tank, led what media called the \"[[Nouvelle Droite]]\" to fame in the late 1970s.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|date=1 June 2001|title=The Ambiguities of the Nouvelle Droite, 1968\u20131999|journal=The European Legacy|volume=6|issue=3|pages=333\u2013334|doi=10.1080/10848770120051349|issn=1084-8770}}</ref> De Benoist became a critic for mainstream right-wing magazines, namely ''[[Valeurs actuelles|Valeurs Actuelles]]'' (from 1970 to 1982) and ''[[Le Figaro Magazine]]'' (from 1977 to 1992),<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=XqoUAQAAIAAJ&q|title=Encyclop\u00e9die politique fran\u00e7aise|last=Ratier|first=Emmanuel|date=1 January 1992|publisher=Faits et documents|isbn=9782909769004|pages=73|language=fr}}</ref> and received in 1978 the [[Prix de l'essai]] from the [[Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]] for his book ''Vu de droite: Anthologie critique des id\u00e9es contemporaines'', which sold 30,000 copies.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=WbTEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT313|title=G\u00e9n\u00e9ration Occident|last=Charpier|first=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|date=31 January 2014|publisher=Le Seuil|isbn=9782021157512|pages=313|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nAlthough de Benoist has stated his retirement from political parties and elections to rather focus on [[Metapolitics|meta-politics]] dates back to 1968,<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>Johnson, Douglas (1995). \"The New Right in France\". In: Luciano Cheles, Ronnie Ferguson, and Michalina Vaughan (eds.) ''The Far Right in Western and Eastern Europe'' (second ed.). London and New York: Longman Group. pp. 238\u2013239</ref> he was a candidate for the far-right micro-party [[Party of New Forces]] during the [[1979 European Parliament election|1979 European elections]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=dqiFAAAAIAAJ|title=Visages de la Nouvelle droite: le GRECE et son histoire|last=Duranton-Crabol|first=Anne-Marie|date=1988|publisher=Presses de la Fondation nationale des sciences politiques|isbn=9782724605617|pages=124|language=fr}}</ref> In the [[1984 European Parliament election in France|1984 election to the European Parliament]], he announced his intention to vote for the [[French Communist Party]], and justified his choice by defining the party as the most credible anti-capitalist, anti-liberal, and anti-American political force then active in France.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|date=1 June 2001|title=The Ambiguities of the Nouvelle Droite, 1968\u20131999|journal=The European Legacy|volume=6|issue=3|pages=343|doi=10.1080/10848770120051349|issn=1084-8770}}</ref>\n\nDe Benoist met [[Aleksandr Dugin|Alexandr Dugin]] in 1989. They soon became close collaborators: de Benoist was invited to Moscow by Dugin in 1992, and the latter presented himself as the correspondent of GRECE in Moscow for a time. The two authors eventually broke their relationship in 1993 after a virulent campaign in French and German media against the \"[[National Bolshevism|red and brown]] threat\" in Russia. While de Benoist acknowledged ideological differences on [[Eurasianism]] and [[Martin Heidegger|Heidegger]], the two of them have maintained regular exchanges since then.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=Coi8BAAAQBAJ|title=In the Tracks of Breivik: Far Right Networks in Northern and Eastern Europe|last=Deland|first=Mats|last2=Minkenberg|first2=Michael|last3=Mays|first3=Christin|date=2014|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|isbn=9783643905420|pages=93\u201394|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Intellectual re-emergence (1994\u2013present) ===\nIn 1979 and 1993, two press campaigns launched in French liberal media against de Benoist,  claiming that he was a \"closet Fascist\" or a \"Nazi\", damaged his reputation and influence in France. They accused him of hiding his racist and anti-egalitarian beliefs in a seemingly acceptable way to the public, by replacing the hierarchy of races with the less suspicious concept of \"[[Ethnopluralism|ethno-pluralism]]\".<ref name=\":11\" /> Although he still frequently comments on politics, de Benoist chose in the early 1990s to focus on his intellectual activity and avoid media attention.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nSince the 2000s onward however, public interest for his works have re-emerged:<ref name=\":5\" /> he has made several media appearances in [[France Culture]], [[Europe 1]], [[Telemadrid]], [[Radio Courtoisie]] or [[Il Giornale]], and his writings have been published in several academic journals like the [[New Left]] [[Telos (journal)|''Telos'']], the [[white nationalist]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Measured Lies: The Bell Curve Examined|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-0-312-17228-2|editor1-last=Gresson|editor1-first=Aaron|edition=1st St. Martin's Griffin|page=39|editor2-last=Kincheloe|editor2-first=Joe L.|editor2-link=Joe L. Kincheloe|editor3-last=Steinberg|editor3-first=Shirley R.|editor3-link=Shirley R. Steinberg|title-link=Measured Lies: The Bell Curve Examined}}</ref> ''[[Mankind Quarterly]]'', the [[Paleoconservatism|paleoconservative]] ''[[Chronicles (magazine)|Chronicles]]'', the nationalist ''[[The Occidental Quarterly|Occidental Quarterly]]'' and the [[Traditionalist School|radical traditionnalist]] ''[[Tyr (journal)|Tyr]]''.<ref>Fran\u00e7ois, St\u00e9phane. \u00ab The gods looked down : la musique \u00ab industrielle \u00bb et le paganisme \u00bb, ''Soci\u00e9t\u00e9s'', vol. n<sup>o</sup> 88, no. 2, 2005, pp. 109\u2013124. ([https://www.cairn.info/revue-societes-2005-2-page-109.htm Read online])</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unz.com/print/author/DeBenoistAlain/|title=Publication|website=The Unz Review|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was one of the adherents to the 2002 ''[[Manifesto Against the Death of the Spirit and the Earth]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal|issue=44|journal=Bulletin d'Histoire Contemporaine de l'Espagne|location=Aix-en-Provence|publisher=[[Publications de l'Universit\u00e9 de Provence|Publications de l\u2019universit\u00e9 de Provence]]|title=Las \"otras\" derechas en la Espa\u00f1a actual. Te\u00f3logos, \"racionalistas\" y neoderechistas|first=Pedro Carlos|last=Gonz\u00e1lez Cuevas|issn=0987-4135|pages=276\u2013277}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.redalyc.org/pdf/181/18153296003.pdf|title=Contra la muerte del esp\u00edritu: \u00faltimos avatares de una nouvelle droite a la espa\u00f1ola|journal=N\u00f3madas. Critical Journal of Social and Juridical Sciences|volume=13|issue=1|year=2006|last=Sanrom\u00e1n|first=Diego L.|issn=1578-6730}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2002 republication of ''Vu de droite'', de Benoist reiterated what he wrote in 1977: the \"greatest\" danger in the world today was the \"progressive disappearance of diversity from the world,\" including biodiversity of animals, cultures and peoples.<ref name=\":5\" /> De Benoist is now the editor of two journals: ''Nouvelle \u00c9cole'' (since 1968), and ''Krisis'' (since 1988).<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=phhhHT64kIMC|title=International Who's Who of Authors and Writers 2004|last=Publications|first=Europa|date=2003|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=9781857431797|pages=49|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the extent of the relationship is debated by scholars, de Benoist and the [[Nouvelle Droite]] have influenced the ideological and political structure of the European [[Identitarian movement|Identitarian Movement]].<ref name=\":022\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=UUSCDwAAQBAJ|title=Key Thinkers of the Radical Right: Behind the New Threat to Liberal Democracy|last=Sedgwick|first=Mark|date=8 January 2019|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190877613|pages=73|language=en|quote=Since the early 1990s, the French New Right has been influential beyond France, especially in Italy, Germany, and Belgium, and has inspired Alexander Dugin in Russia. Part of the American radical Right and \"Alt Right\" also claims to have been inspired by de Benoist\u2019s writings. Although this is questionable, de Benoist and Dominique Venner are also seen as the forefathers of the \"identitarian\" movement in Europe.}}</ref><ref name=\"LionsNorth2\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=AHmuDQAAQBAJ|title=Lions of the North: Sounds of the New Nordic Radical Nationalism|last=Teitelbaum|first=Benjamin R.|date=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190212599|pages=46|language=en}}</ref> Part of the [[alt-right]] also claims to have been inspired by de Benoist's writings.<ref name=\":022\" />\n\n==Views==\n\nFrom being close to pro-colonial movements and adopting an ethnobiological perspective at the beginning of his writings in the 1960s,<ref>Alain de Benoist: \"What makes a population move towards greater quality is that valuable men, the elites, can in turn procreate and transmit, according to the laws of heredity, their exceptional abilities and gifts.\" (Avec ou sans Dieu ?, 1970, p. 88)</ref><ref name=\":15\" /> when he endorsed [[apartheid]] with Gilles Fournier as the \"last outpost of the West\" at a time of \"decolonisation and international negrification\",<ref name=\":9\" /> de Benoist gradually moved towards a [[Third-Worldism|defense of the Third-World]] against [[American imperialism]] and a more cultural definition of \"difference\", theorized in his concept of [[ethnopluralism]]. De Benoist is also an ardent critic of [[globalisation]], unrestricted [[Immigration|mass immigration]], [[liberalism]], [[Postmodernity|postmodern society]] and what he calls the \"ideology of sameness\".<ref name=\":52\" /><ref name=\":11\" /> Scholars question if this evolution in de Benoist's concepts should be considered a sincere ideological detachment from a far-right activist youth,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liberation.fr/france/2015/03/09/alain-de-benoist-n-a-rien-a-voir-avec-le-fn_1217324|title=Pol\u00e9mique Valls-Onfray : Les n\u00e9odroitiers ont contribu\u00e9 \u00e0 structurer le FN, sans en devenir la matrice|last=Fran\u00e7ois|first=St\u00e9phane|authorlink=St\u00e9phane Fran\u00e7ois|date=9 March 2015|website=[[Lib\u00e9ration]]|language=fr|access-date=18 August 2019}}</ref> or rather a meta-political strategy to reshape unegalitarian ideas into acceptable differentialist terms.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bar-On|first=Tamir|date=2014|title=A Response to Alain de Benoist|journal=Journal for the Study of Radicalism|volume=8|issue=2|pages=123\u2013168|doi=10.14321/jstudradi.8.2.0123|issn=1930-1189|jstor=10.14321/jstudradi.8.2.0123|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/18859076e17881ddf6b4ab222967648e173eb3f9}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taguieff|first=Pierre-Andr\u00e9|author-link=Pierre-Andr\u00e9 Taguieff|date=1993|title=Origines et m\u00e9tamorphoses de la Nouvelle Droite|journal=Vingti\u00e8me Si\u00e8cle. Revue d'histoire|issue=40|pages=3\u201322|doi=10.2307/3770354|issn=0294-1759|jstor=3770354}}</ref>\n\nPolitical scientist [[Jean-Yves Camus]] describes the key idea of de Benoist's writings in those terms: \"through the use of [[Metapolitics|meta-politics]], to think the ways and means that are necessary in order for European civilization, based on the cultural values shared on the continent until the advent of globalization, to thrive and be perpetuated.\"<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=UUSCDwAAQBAJ|title=Key Thinkers of the Radical Right: Behind the New Threat to Liberal Democracy|last=Sedgwick|first=Mark|date=8 January 2019|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190877613|pages=75\u201376|language=en}}</ref> Though he embodies the core values of GRECE and the Nouvelle Droite, de Benoist\u2019s works are not always identical to those of other thinkers of the movements. He for instance disavowed [[Guillaume Faye]]'s \"strongly racist\" ideas regarding Muslims after the publication of ''The Colonization of Europe: Speaking Truth about Immigration and Islam'' in 2000.<ref name=\":12\" /> De Benoist is indeed opposed to political violence, stating that he had been building \"a school of thought, not a political movement.\"<ref>France;Ideas and bombs The Economist 23 August 1980</ref>\n\n=== Identity ===\nInspired by [[Martin Buber]]'s [[philosophy of dialogue]] and his ''[[I and Thou|Ich und Du]]'' concept, de Benoist defined \"identity\" as a \"dialogical\" phenomenon in ''We and the Others'' (\"Nous et les autres\", 2006). According to him, one's identity is made of two components: the \"objective part\" that comes from one\u2019s background (ethnicity, religion, family, nationality), and the \"subjective part\", freely chosen by the individual. Identity is therefore a process in constant evolution, rather than a completely fixed notion.<ref name=\":12\" /> In 1992, he consequently dismissed the [[National Rally (France)|Front National]] use of ethnopluralism, on the grounds that it portrayed \"difference as an absolute, whereas, by definition, it exists only relationally.\"<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=_j5YDgAAQBAJ|title=Far-Right Politics in Europe|last=Camus|first=Jean-Yves|last2=Lebourg|first2=Nicolas|date=20 March 2017|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674971530|pages=124|language=en}}</ref><ref>Sharon Waxman, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1993-12-13/features/9312130011_1_intellectuals-debate-anti-immigrant \u2033Europe's Left And Right Are Too Divided To Even Talk About It\u2033], Chicago Tribune, 13 December 1993. Retrieved 21 June 2017.</ref> De Benoist believes that knowledge of ethnic and religious traditions is a duty, which must be passed on to following generation, and is critical of the idea of a moral imperative to [[cosmopolitanism]].<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=UUSCDwAAQBAJ|title=Key Thinkers of the Radical Right: Behind the New Threat to Liberal Democracy|last=Sedgwick|first=Mark|date=8 January 2019|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190877613|pages=78|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIf scholars like [[Pierre-Andr\u00e9 Taguieff]] have labeled the [[Nouvelle Droite]] a form of \"mixophobia\", due to its focus on the concept of \"difference\", de Benoist has also criticized what he calls \"the pathology of identity\", that is to say the political use of identity by the [[Right-wing populism|populist Right]] in order to push an \"us versus them\" debate escorted by \"[systematic] and [irrational] hating\". The difficulty of understanding de Benoist\u2019s views on identity lies in the fact that his writings have experienced multiple re-synthesis since the 1960s. In 1974, he said: \"there is no superior race. All races are superior and each of them has its own genius\".<ref name=\":14\" /> Suspicions have arisen of a subtle meta-political guise designed with the aim of re-establishing the original fascist idea around a new framework, and de Benoist has been influenced by [[Carl Schmitt]]'s distinction between friend and enemy as the core issue of politics. He however sees immigrants as eventually victims of [[globalization]], and also explained that immigration was first of all a consequence of big companies being greedy for profits and preferring to import cheap labor.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\n=== Ethnopluralism ===\nDe Benoist rejects the [[nation state]] and [[nationalism]], on the ground that both liberalism and nationalism eventually derive from the same [[metaphysics]] of [[subjectivity]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=UUSCDwAAQBAJ|title=Key Thinkers of the Radical Right: Behind the New Threat to Liberal Democracy|last=Sedgwick|first=Mark|date=8 January 2019|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190877613|pages=76|language=en}}</ref> and that the centralized and \"[[Jacobin]]\" state [[France|French Republic]] had destroyed regional identities in the project of \"one and indivisible\" France.<ref name=\":5\" /> He stands instead for the political autonomy of each and every group, favoring an integral federalism built on the principle of subsidiarity, that would transcend the nation state and give way to regional identities and a common continental one at once.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=De Benoist|first=Alain|date=2014|title=Alain de Benoist Answers Tamir Bar-On|journal=Journal for the Study of Radicalism|volume=8|issue=1|pages=141\u2013168|doi=10.14321/jstudradi.8.1.0141|jstor=10.14321/jstudradi.8.1.0141|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/6407098cda6c7f46f6ae2890aa54f0eff2261409}}</ref>\n\n=== Liberalism ===\nDe Benoist is a critic of the primacy of [[Individual and group rights|individual rights]], an ideology he sees embodied in [[humanism]], the [[French Revolution]], and the [[Founding Fathers of the United States|American Founding Fathers]]. While not a [[Marxism|Marxist]], de Benoist has been influenced by the communist analysis of the nature of capitalism and conflicting class interests, exposed by [[Karl Marx]] in ''Das Kapital.'' As a result, another of his core ideas is that the world is facing the \"hegemony of capital\" and the \"pursuit of self-interest\", two typical trends of the [[Postmodernity|postmodern era]]. According to Jean-Yves Camus however, if de Benoist can share anti-capitalist analysis with leftists, the nature of his goal is indeed different, as de Benoist considers the unlimited expansion of the free market and [[consumerism]] as key contributors to the erasure of peoples' identities. Furthermore, although he aknowledges their existence, he does not makes an essential distinction between the \"[[working class]]\" and the \"[[bourgeoise]]\", but rather between the \"new dominant class\" and the \"people\".<ref name=\":12\" /> In 1991, his magazine ''El\u00e9ments'' described via its editorial staff how \"too systematic anti-egalitarianism [could] lead to [[social Darwinism]], which might justify [[free-market economy]]\".<ref name=\":14\" />\n\n=== United States ===\nDe Benoist is opposed to the [[Liberalism in the United States|American liberal]] idea of a [[melting pot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/EuropeanSonAnInterviewWithAlainDeBenoist|title=European Son : An Interview with Alain de Benoist|format=PDF|accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref> A critic of the [[United States]], he has been quoted as saying: \"Some people do not accept the thought of one day having to wear the Red Army cap. In fact, it is a terrible prospect. However, this is not a reason to tolerate the idea of one day having to spend what we have left to live on by eating hamburgers in Brooklyn.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liberation.fr/france/2016/04/08/la-passion-russe-de-l-extreme-droite_1444969|title=La passion russe de l'extr\u00eame droite|date=8 April 2016|website=Lib\u00e9ration.fr|language=fr|access-date=18 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Orientations pour des ann\u00e9es d\u00e9cisives|last=De Benoist|first=Alain|publisher=Labyrinthe|year=1982|location=Paris|pages=76|quote=Certains ne se r\u00e9signent pas \u00e0 la pens\u00e9e d\u2019avoir un jour \u00e0 porter la casquette de l\u2019Arm\u00e9e rouge. De fait, c\u2019est une perspective affreuse. Nous ne pouvons pas, pour autant, supporter l\u2019id\u00e9e d\u2019avoir un jour \u00e0 passer ce qui nous reste \u00e0 vivre en mangeant des hamburgers du c\u00f4t\u00e9 de Brooklyn.}}</ref> In 1991, he complained that European supporters of the first [[Gulf War]] were \"collaborators of the American order.\"<ref>Rone Tempest, [http://articles.latimes.com/print/1991-02-15/news/mn-1225_1_secret-agenda \"French Revive a Pastime: Fretting About U.S. 'Imperialism' : Reaction: Talk of 'secret agendas' surfaces on the left and the right. Some chafe at their country's secondary role in the Gulf. Others worry about diminished European influence,\"] ''Los Angeles Times'', 15 February 1991.</ref>\n\n=== Islam ===\nDe Benoist has supported ties with [[Islamic culture]] in the 1980s,<ref>Under cover story The Guardian (London) 14 August 1987.</ref> on the grounds that the relationship would be distinct from what he saw as the consumerism and materialism of American society, as well as the bureaucracy and repression of the [[Soviet Union]].<ref>The disharmonic convergence: the far left and the far right as strange bedfellows,s Whole Earth Review 22 June 1988</ref>\n\n=== Paganism and Christianity ===\nHe also opposes [[Christianity]] as inherently intolerant, theocratic and bent on persecution.<ref>Intolerance, American-Style;Given This Country's History of Religious Animosities, Thomas Fleming Writes Pittsburgh Post-Gazette (Pennsylvania) 21 December 1997</ref>\n\n== Influences ==\nDe Benoist's influences include [[Antonio Gramsci]],<ref>\u2033The Marcuse factor\u2033, Modern Age, 22 March 2005.</ref> [[Ernst J\u00fcnger]], [[Martin Buber]], [[Jean Baudrillard]], [[Georges Dum\u00e9zil]], [[Ernest Renan]], [[Jos\u00e9 Ortega y Gasset]], [[Vilfredo Pareto]], [[Karl Marx]],<ref name=\":12\" /> [[Guy Debord]], [[Arnold Gehlen]], [[St\u00e9phane Lupasco]], [[Helmut Schelsky]], [[Konrad Lorenz]], the [[Conservative Revolution]]naries, the [[non-conformists of the 1930s]],<ref>\u2033Posthistoire: Has History Come to an End?\u2033, CLIO, 1 January 1994.</ref> [[Johann Gottfried Herder]], [[Johannes Althusius]], interwar [[Austromarxism|Austro-Marxists]],<ref name=\":12\" /> and [[communitarian]] philosophers such as [[Alasdair MacIntyre]] and [[Charles Taylor (philosopher)|Charles Taylor]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Communitarian Third Way: Alexandre Marc and Ordre Nouveau, 1930\u20132000|last1=Hellman|first1=John|date=2002|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press|page=196}}</ref>\n\n==Critics==\n\nHis critics, such as [[Thomas Sheehan (academic)|Thomas Sheehan]], argue that de Benoist has developed a novel restatement of [[fascism]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sheehan |first=Thomas |title=Myth and Violence: The Fascism of Julius Evola and Alain de Benoist |journal=[[Social Research]]| volume=48 |issue=1 |date=Spring 1981 |pages=45\u201373 | quote= Pages 66\u201367: To summarize: De Benoist's fascism is at odds with Evola's metaphysics but agrees with his social and political philosophy.... [F]or de Benoist, the organic State is an ideal that men can set for themselves and perhaps, with force, establish.}}</ref> [[Roger Griffin]], using an [[ideal type]] definition of fascism which includes \"populist ultra-nationalism\" and \"[[palingenesis]]\" (heroic rebirth), argues that the [[Nouvelle Droite]] draws on such fascist ideologues as [[Armin Mohler]] in a way that allows Nouvelle Droite ideologues such as de Benoist to claim a \"metapolitical\" stance, but which nonetheless has residual fascist ideological elements.<ref name=\"Griffin\">{{cite journal|author=Griffin, Roger|year=2000|title=Between metapolitics and apoliteia: the Nouvelle Droite's strategy for conserving the fascist vision in the 'interregnum'|journal=Modern & Contemporary France|volume=8|issue=1|pages= 35\u201353|doi=10.1080/096394800113349}}</ref> De Benoist's critics also claim his views recall [[Nazism|Nazi]] attempts to replace German Christianity with its own paganism.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Marx, Moses, and the Pagans in the Secular City|last=Sunic|first=Tomislav|journal=CLIO|volume=24|issue=2|date=Winter 1995|pages=169\u2013188|quote=In the age that is heavily laced with the Biblical message, many modern pagan thinkers, for their criticism of biblical monotheism, have been attacked and stigmatized either as unrepentant atheists or as spiritual standard-bearers of fascism. Particularly Nietzsche, Heidegger, and more recently Alain de Benoist came under attack for allegedly espousing the philosophy which, for their contemporary detractors, recalled the earlier national socialist attempts to \"dechristianize\" and \"repaganize\" Germany. <sup>See notably the works by Alfred Rosenberg, ''Der Mythus des 20. Jahrhunderts''(M\u00fcnchen: Hoheneichen Verlag, 1933). Also worth noting is the name of Wilhelm Hauer, ''Deutscher Gottschau'' (Stuttgart: Karl Gutbrod, 1934), who significantly popularized Indo-European mythology among national socialists: on pages 240\u201354 Hauer discusses the difference between Judeo-Christian Semitic beliefs and European paganism.</sup>}}</ref> They note that de Benoist's rejection of the French Revolution's legacy and the allegedly \"abstract\" Rights of Man ties him to the same [[Counter-Enlightenment]] right-wing tradition as counter-revolutionary [[Legitimists]], fascists, [[Vichy France|Vichyites]] and integral nationalists.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Backes |first1=Uwe |last2=Moreau |first2=Patrick |title=The Extreme Right in Europe: Current Trends and Perspectives |date=2011 |publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht |page=335}}</ref>\n\n== Private life ==\nA [[Modern Paganism|neo-pagan]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=de Halleux|first=Andr\u00e9|date=1992|title=D\u00e9m\u00e8tre Th\u00e9raios (\u00e9d.), Quelle religion pour l'Europe ? Un d\u00e9bat sur l'identit\u00e9 religieuse des peuples europ\u00e9ens. 1990|url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/thlou_0080-2654_1992_num_23_2_2562_t1_0255_0000_2|journal=Revue Th\u00e9ologique de Louvain|volume=23|issue=2|pages=255\u2013256}}</ref> de Benoist married Doris Christians in 1971 and has two children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whoswho.fr/bio/alain-de-benoist_11216|title=Alain de Benoist \u2013 Who's Who|website=www.whoswho.fr|language=fr|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> He is a member of the [[high IQ society]] [[Mensa International|Mensa]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://phdn.org/negation/taguieff-heritage-nazi-1981.html|title=Pierre-Andr\u00e9 Taguieff, L'H\u00e9ritage nazi. Des Nouvelles Droites europ\u00e9ennes \u00e0 la litt\u00e9rature niant le g\u00e9nocide|website=phdn.org|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> and owns the largest private library in France,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.franceculture.fr/emissions/le-tete-tete/alain-de-benoist|title=Alain de Benoist|website=France Culture|language=fr|access-date=31 July 2019|quote=Il a la plus grande biblioth\u00e8que priv\u00e9e de France qui compte plus de cent cinquante mille ouvrages.}}</ref> with an estimate of 150,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.causeur.fr/alain-de-benoist-un-intellectuel-aux-antipodes-17355|title=Alain de Benoist : un intellectuel aux antipodes|last=Causeur.fr|last2=Boughezala|first2=Daoud|date=6 May 2012|website=Causeur|language=fr-FR|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> to 250,000 books.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\n==Selected works==\n\n===French===\n\n* ''Salan devant l'opinion'' (sous le pseudonyme de Fabrice Laroche) (Saint-Just, 1963).\n* ''Les Indo-Europ\u00e9ens'' (G.E.D., 1966).\n* ''L'Empirisme logique et la Philosophie du Cercle de Vienne'' (Nouvelle \u00c9cole, 1970).\n* ''[[Friedrich Nietzsche|Nietzsche]]: Morale et \u00ab Grande Politique \u00bb'' (GRECE, 1973).\n* ''[[Konrad Lorenz]] et l'\u00c9thologie moderne'' (Nouvelle \u00c9cole, 1975).\n* ''Vu de droite. Anthologie critique des id\u00e9es contemporaines'' (Copernic, 1977). ([[Prix de l'essai|grand prix de l'essai de l'Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]] 1978)\n* ''Les Bretons'' (Les Cahiers de ''la Bretagne r\u00e9elle'', n\u00b0396 ''bis'', 1978).\n* ''Les Id\u00e9es \u00e0 l'endroit'' (Libres-[[Jean-Edern Hallier|Hallier]], 1978).\n* ''Le Guide pratique des pr\u00e9noms'' (\u00ab Robert de Herte \u00bb et {{sic}} Alain de Benoist), coll. \u00ab Hors-s\u00e9rie d'\"Enfants-Magazine\" \u00bb (Publications Groupe M\u00e9dia, 1979).\n* ''Comment peut-on \u00eatre pa\u00efen ?'' (Albin Michel, 1981).\n* ''Les Traditions d'Europe'' (Paris: Labyrinthe, 1982).\n* ''Orientations pour des ann\u00e9es d\u00e9cisives'' (Labyrinthe, 1982).\n* ''F\u00eater No\u00ebl. L\u00e9gendes et Traditions'' (Atlas-Edena, 1982).\n* ''D\u00e9mocratie : le probl\u00e8me'' (Labyrinthe, 1985)\n* (in collaboration with Andre B\u00e9jin & Julien Freund) ''Racismes, Antiracismes'' (Paris: Librairie des M\u00e9ridiens, 1986)\n* (with Thomas Molnar) ''L'\u00e9clipse du sacr\u00e9: discours et r\u00e9sponses'' (Paris: Table ronde, 1986)\n* ''Europe, Tiers monde, m\u00eame combat'' ([[\u00c9ditions Robert Laffont|Robert Laffont]], 1986).\n* ''Le Grain de sable. Jalons pour une fin de si\u00e8cle'' (Labyrinthe, 1994).\n* ''Nationalisme : Ph\u00e9nom\u00e9nologie et Critique'' (GRECE, 1994).\n* ''D\u00e9mocratie repr\u00e9sentative et D\u00e9mocratie participative'' (GRECE, 1994).\n* ''Nietzsche et la R\u00e9volution conservatrice'' (GRECE, 1994).\n* ''L'Empire int\u00e9rieur'' (Fata Morgana, 1995).\n* ''La Ligne de mire. Discours aux citoyens europ\u00e9ens, t. 1 : 1972\u20131987'' (Labyrinthe, 1995).\n* ''Famille et Soci\u00e9t\u00e9. Origine, Histoire, Actualit\u00e9'' (Labyrinthe, 1996).\n* ''La Ligne de mire. Discours aux citoyens europ\u00e9ens, t. 2 : 1988\u20131995'' (Labyrinthe, 1996).\n* ''[[Louis-Ferdinand C\u00e9line|C\u00e9line]] et l'Allemagne, 1933\u20131945. Une mise au point'' (Le Bulletin c\u00e9linien, 1996).\n* ''Horizon 2000. Trois entretiens avec Alain de Benoist'' (GRECE, 1996).\n* ''La L\u00e9gende de [[Clovis I|Clovis]]'' (Cercle Ernest Renan, 1996).\n* ''Indo-Europ\u00e9ens : \u00e0 la recherche du foyer d'origine'' (Nouvelle \u00c9cole, 1997).\n* ''[[Ernst J\u00fcnger]]. Une bio-bibliographie'' (Guy Tr\u00e9daniel, 1997).\n* ''Communisme et Nazisme. 25 r\u00e9flexions sur le totalitarisme au XXe si\u00e8cle'' (Labyrinthe, 1998).\n* ''L'\u00c9cume et les Galets. 1991\u20131999 : dix ans d'actualit\u00e9 vue d'ailleurs'' (Labyrinthe, 2000).\n* ''J\u00e9sus sous l'\u0153il critique des historiens'' (Cercle Ernest Renan, 2000).\n* ''Bibliographie d'Henri B\u00e9raud'' (Association r\u00e9taise des Amis d'Henri B\u00e9raud, 2000).\n* ''Derni\u00e8re Ann\u00e9e. Notes pour conclure le si\u00e8cle'' (L'\u00c2ge d'Homme, 2001).\n* ''[[J\u00e9sus]] et ses Fr\u00e8res'' (Cercle Ernest Renan, 2001).\n* ''Louis Rougier. Sa vie, son \u0153uvre'' (Cercle Ernest Renan, 2002).\n* ''[[Charles Maurras]] et [[l'Action fran\u00e7aise]]. Une bibliographie'', BCM, 2002\n* ''Qu'est-ce qu'un militant ?'' (sous le pseudonyme de Fabrice Laroche, r\u00e9\u00e9dition d'un article paru en 1963) (Ars Magna, 2003).\n* ''Critiques-Th\u00e9oriques'' (L'\u00c2ge d'Homme, 2003).\n* ''Au-del\u00e0 des droits de l'homme. Pour d\u00e9fendre les libert\u00e9s'' (\u00e9ditions Krisis, 2004).\n* ''Bibliographie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale des droites fran\u00e7aises. 1, [[Arthur de Gobineau]], [[Gustave Le Bon]], [[\u00c9douard Drumont]], [[Maurice Barr\u00e8s]], [[Pierre Drieu La Rochelle]], [[Henry de Montherlant]], [[Thierry Maulnier]], [[Julien Freund]]'' (\u00c9ditions Dualpha, coll. \u00ab Patrimoine des lettres \u00bb, Coulommiers, 2004), 609 p.\n* ''Bibliographie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale des droites fran\u00e7aises. 2, [[Georges Sorel]], [[Charles Maurras]], [[Georges Valois]], [[Abel Bonnard]], [[Henri B\u00e9raud]], [[Louis Rougier]], [[Lucien Rebatet]], [[Robert Brasillach]]'' (\u00c9ditions Dualpha, coll. \u00ab Patrimoine des lettres \u00bb, Coulommiers, 2004), 472 p.\n* ''Bibliographie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale des droites fran\u00e7aises. 3, [[Louis de Bonald]], [[Alexis de Tocqueville]], [[Georges Vacher de Lapouge]], [[L\u00e9on Daudet]], [[Jacques Bainville]], [[Ren\u00e9 Benjamin]], [[Henri Massis]], [[Georges Bernanos]], [[Maurice Bard\u00e8che]], [[Jean Cau (writer)|Jean Cau]]'' (\u00c9ditions Dualpha, coll. \u00ab Patrimoine des lettres \u00bb, Coulommiers, 2005), 648 p.\n* ''Bibliographie g\u00e9n\u00e9rale des droites fran\u00e7aises. 4, [[Joseph de Maistre]], [[Ernest Renan]], [[:fr:Jules Soury|Jules Soury]], [[Charles P\u00e9guy]], [[Alphonse de Chateaubriant]], [[Jacques Benoist-M\u00e9chin]], [[Gustave Thibon]], Saint-Loup ([[Marc Augier]]), [[Louis Pauwels]]'' (\u00c9ditions Dualpha, coll. \u00ab Patrimoine des lettres \u00bb, Coulommiers, 2005), 736 p.\n* ''J\u00e9sus et ses Fr\u00e8res, et autres \u00e9crits sur le christianisme, le paganisme et la religion'' (\u00e9ditions Les Amis d'Alain de Benoist, 2006).\n* ''C'est-\u00e0-dire. Entretiens-T\u00e9moignages-Explications'' (2 volumes) (\u00e9ditions Les Amis d'Alain de Benoist, 2006).\n* ''Nous et les autres. Probl\u00e9matique de l'identit\u00e9'' (\u00e9ditions Krisis, 2006).\n* ''[[Carl Schmitt]] actuel'' (\u00e9ditions Krisis, 2007).\n* ''Demain, la d\u00e9croissance ! Penser l'\u00e9cologie jusqu'au bout'' (Edite, 2007).\n* [http://www.revue-elements.com/livres-Textes-Politiques-1919-1945.html ''Dictionnaire des pr\u00e9noms : d'hier et d'aujourd'hui, d'ici et d'ailleurs''] (Jean Picollec, 2009).\n* ''M\u00e9moire vive / Entretiens avec Fran\u00e7ois Bousquet'' (\u00c9ditions de Fallois, Collection \u00ab Litt\u00e9rature \u00bb, 2 mai 2012).\n* ''Edouard Berth ou le socialisme h\u00e9ro\u00efque. Sorel, Maurras, Lenine'' (Pard\u00e8s, 2013).\n* ''Les D\u00e9mons du Bien, Du nouvel ordre moral \u00e0 l'id\u00e9ologie du genre'' (Pierre-Guillaume de Roux, 2013).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* ''[[Fascism (book)|Fascism]]'', edited by [[Roger Griffin]] (1995), pp.&nbsp;346\u2013348.\n* ''[[The Beast Reawakens]]'' by [[Martin A. Lee]] (1997), pp.&nbsp;208\u2013213.\n* ''[[Biographical Dictionary of the Extreme Right Since 1890]]'' (1990), edited by [[Philip Rees]], pp.&nbsp;29\u201330.\n\n==Further reading==\n* Jonathan Marcus, ''The National Front and French Politics'', New York: New York University Press, 1995, pp.&nbsp;22\u20134, 151.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official}}\n\n{{Alt-right footer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benoist, Alain de}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alt-right]]\n[[Category:Alt-right writers]]\n[[Category:People from Tours, France]]\n[[Category:French political philosophers]]\n[[Category:New Right (Europe)]]\n[[Category:Geopoliticians]]\n[[Category:French political writers]]\n[[Category:French neopagans]]\n[[Category:Identitarian movement in France]]\n[[Category:20th-century French philosophers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:French male essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century French essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century French essayists]]\n[[Category:Critics of Christianity]]\n[[Category:Anti-consumerists]]\n[[Category:Degrowth advocates]]\n[[Category:Prix de l'essai laureates]]\n[[Category:20th-century French male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century French male writers]]\n[[Category:Neopagan writers]]\n[[Category:Pan-European nationalism]]\n[[Category:Neopaganism in France]]\n[[Category:Indo-Europeanists]]\n[[Category:French nationalists]]\n[[Category:Runologists]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, replaced: traditionnalist \u2192 traditionalist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alain_de_Benoist"}
{"title_page": "Isar-ul-Haq Qasmi", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious biography\n|name = Haq Nawaz Jhangvi\n| birth_date          = {{Birth year|1964}}\n| birth_place         = [[Samundri]], [[Punjab, Pakistan]]\n| death_date          = {{Death year and age|1991|1964}}\n}}\n'''Isar ul Haq Qasmi''' (who died in 1991) was a Pakistani Islamic cleric, preacher and a member of [[Sipah-e-Sahaba Pakistan]]. He had been member of the National Assembly of Pakistan between 1990 and 1993 representing Jhang constituency.\n\nBorn in 1964 to a family which migrated from [[Ambala]] and settled in [[Samundri]], Punjab, at the Partition, with a father who worked in the [[Middle East]] for years (like many SSP members), he was educated in three madrasas in [[Lahore]], and at first went for a business career but then decided to become khatib (preacher) in an [[Okara, Pakistan|Okara]] mosque from 1985 onward, where he also established a madrasa, and he would soon gain a reputation for his clashes with the  local police, before moving to [[Jhang]] at the request of [[Haq Nawaz Jhangvi]], to preach in one of the market-towns of the district.<ref>Zaman, Muhammad Qasim. \u201cSectarianism in Pakistan: The Radicalization of Shi'i and Sunni Identities.\u201d ''Modern Asian Studies'', vol. 32, no. 3, 1998, pp. 710-711.</ref> \n\nHe was elected to the [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] as a candidate of [[Islami Jamhoori Ittehad]] (IJI) in the [[1990 Pakistani general election]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.electionpakistani.com/ge1990/NA-68.htm|title=NA-68 Jhang III Election Result 1990|first=created by|last=MASK|website=www.electionpakistani.com}}</ref> He received 62,486 and defeated Nawab Amanullah Khan Sial of [[Pakistan Democratic Alliance]] (PDA).<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nHe was murdered in 1991 during a by-election in [[Jhang]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newslinemagazine.com/magazine/in-death-as-in-life/|title=In Death, as in Life - Newsline|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Azam Tariq (religious leader)|Azam Tariq]]\n* [[Haq Nawaz Jhangvi]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Qasmi, Isar ul Haq}}\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Islamic religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Islamists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 1990\u20131993]]\n[[Category:People from Jhang District]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Pakistani people]]\n[[Category:Assassinated religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Pakistani far-right politicians]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Isar ul Haq Qasmi''' (who died in 1991) was a Pakistani Islamic cleric, preacher and a member of [[Sipah-e-Sahaba Pakistan]]. He had been member of the National Assembly of Pakistan between 1990 and 1993 representing Jhang constituency.\n\nBorn in 1964 to a family which migrated from [[Ambala]] and settled in [[Samundri]], Punjab, at the Partition, with a father who worked in the [[Middle East]] for years (like many SSP members), he was educated in three madrasas in [[Lahore]], and at first went for a business career but then decided to become khatib (preacher) in an [[Okara, Pakistan|Okara]] mosque from 1985 onward, where he also established a madrasa, and he would soon gain a reputation for his clashes with the  local police, before moving to [[Jhang]] at the request of [[Haq Nawaz Jhangvi]], to preach in one of the market-towns of the district.<ref>Zaman, Muhammad Qasim. \u201cSectarianism in Pakistan: The Radicalization of Shi'i and Sunni Identities.\u201d ''Modern Asian Studies'', vol. 32, no. 3, 1998, pp. 710-711.</ref> \n\nHe was elected to the [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] as a candidate of [[Islami Jamhoori Ittehad]] (IJI) in the [[1990 Pakistani general election]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.electionpakistani.com/ge1990/NA-68.htm|title=NA-68 Jhang III Election Result 1990|first=created by|last=MASK|website=www.electionpakistani.com}}</ref> He received 62,486 and defeated Nawab Amanullah Khan Sial of [[Pakistan Democratic Alliance]] (PDA).<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nHe was murdered in 1991 during a by-election in [[Jhang]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newslinemagazine.com/magazine/in-death-as-in-life/|title=In Death, as in Life - Newsline|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Azam Tariq (religious leader)|Azam Tariq]]\n* [[Haq Nawaz Jhangvi]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Qasmi, Isar ul Haq}}\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Islamic religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Islamists]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 1990\u20131993]]\n[[Category:People from Jhang District]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Pakistani people]]\n[[Category:Assassinated religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Pakistani far-right politicians]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Arslan-San", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isar-ul-Haq_Qasmi"}
{"title_page": "Calamus bousigonii", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|image =\n|genus = Calamus (palm)\n|species = bousigonii\n|authority = [[Odoardo Beccari|Becc.]], Rec. Bot. Surv. India ii. 209 (1902)<ref>{{cite web |title=Calamus bousigonii Becc. |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/664998-1 |website=International Plant Name Index (IPNI) |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"powo\" />}}\n\n'''''Calamus bousigonii''''', is a [[liana]], a climbing plant, and part of the [[Arecaceae]], or palm, family. It is a member of the subfamily [[Calamoideae]], whose members are usually called [[rattan]]s in English,\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThis [[species]], ''Calamus bousigonii'' Becc., has 2 [[subspecies]], ''Calamus bousigonii'' subsp. ''bousigonii'' and ''Calamus bousigonii'' subsp. ''smitinandii'' [[John Dransfield|J.Dransf.]], Kew Bull. 55(3): 713 (2000)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dransfield |first1=John |title=Calamus bousigonii |journal=Kew Bulletin |date=2000 |volume=55 |issue=3 |pages=711\u20136 |doi=10.2307/4118788}}</ref><ref name=\"powo\">{{cite web |title=Calamus bousigonii Pierre ex Becc. |url=http://powo.science.kew.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:664998-1 |website=Plants of the World Online (POWO) |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"cbss\">{{cite web |title=Calamus bousigonii subsp. smitinandii J.Dransf.|url=http://powo.science.kew.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:1016846-1|website=Plants of the World Online (POWO) |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\nThe subspecies ''smitinandii'' \"is named for Tem Smitinand (1920-95), Thai botanist extraordinary, who often gave me much encouragement in my studies of Thai palms\", [[John Dransfield]]<ref group=note>please see [[Trias (plant)|Trias]], [[Uncifera]], [[Dipterocarpaceae]], [[Smilax glabra]], [[Gaultheria]] and [[Gastrochilus]] for some contributions to botany by Smitinand referenced on Wikipedia</ref><ref name=\"palmss\">{{cite web |title=Calamus bousigonii subsp. smitinandii J.Dransf., Kew Bull. 55: 713 (2000) |url=http://www.palmweb.org/cdm_dataportal/taxon/9f122273-0ca9-4f94-941a-085ce97c7a6e |website=PALMweb |publisher=palmweb.org |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\nThis page will discuss the species, but note subspecies differences.\n\n==Common names==\nThe plant's names include ''wai huadio'' (Thailand),<ref name=\"evans\">{{cite journal |last1=Evans |first1=Tom D. |last2=Sengdala |first2=Khamphone |last3=Thammavong |first3=Banxa |last4=Viengkham |first4=Oulathong V. |last5=[[John Dransfield]] |title=A Synopsis of the Rattans (Arecaceae: Calamoideae) of Laos and Neighbouring Parts of Indochina |journal=Kew Bulletin |date=2002 |volume=57 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201384 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/4110822 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> ''phdau ar\u00e9:ch'' or ''phdav arech'' (''phdau''=rattan, [[Khmer language|Khmer]]),<ref name=\"dyphon\">{{cite book |last1=[[Pauline Dy Phon]] |title=Plants Utilised In Cambodia/Plantes utilis\u00e9es au Cambodge |date=2000 |publisher=Imprimerie Olympic |location=Phnom Penh |page=121 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=InD2RAAACAAJ}}</ref><ref name=\"evans\" /> and ''may cun'' (''may'' is common to rattan species, Vietnam)<ref name=\"ninh\">{{cite journal |last1=Ninh Khac Ban |last2=Regalado |first2=Jacinto |last3=Nguyen Phu Hung |last4=Nguyen Quoc Dung |last5=Bui My Binh |last6=Tran Phuong Anh |title=Rattan resource of Bach Ma National Park, Thua Thien Hue province |journal=Agricultural Review |date=2005 |volume=14 |pages=1\u20136 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Ninh_Ban/publication/265034386_Rattan_resource_of_Bach_Ma_National_Park_Thua_Thien_Hue_province/links/543c9a8e0cf20af5cfbf6d33.pdf |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\nThe ''smitinandii'' subspecies is called ''wai sae ma'' (\u0e2b\u0e27\u0e32\u0e22\u0e41\u0e0b\u0e48\u0e21\u0e49\u0e32) in [[Trang Province]], southern Thailand.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=[[John Dransfield]] PONGSATTAYAPIPAT |last2=Barfod |first2=A. S. |last3=Pongsattayapipat |first3=R. |title=A preliminary checklist to Thai Palms |journal=Thai For. Bull. (Bot.) |date=2004 |volume=32 |pages=32\u201372 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Anders_Barfod2/publication/256388501_A_preliminary_checklist_to_Thai_Palms/links/00b49522f06df71c22000000/A-preliminary-checklist-to-Thai-Palms.pdf |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThe species grows in [[Thailand]], [[Cambodia]] and southern [[Vietnam]], and possibly northern peninsular [[Malaysia]].<ref name=\"evans\" /><ref name=\"palmsb\">{{cite web |title=Calamus bousigonii subsp. bousigonii |url=http://www.palmweb.org/cdm_dataportal/taxon/51848629-7a77-4c05-be1b-692620d6fc38 |website=PALMweb |publisher=palmweb.org |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"powo\" /> The subspecies ''bousigonii'' is recorded the same, however Dransfield regards the population in peninsular Thailand (and presumably that in Malaysia) as the ''smitinandii'' subspecies.<ref name=\"palmsb\" /><ref name=\"cbss\" /> The conservation status of the species is unknown, however the population in peninisular Thailand is probably not threatened.\n\n==Ecology==\nThe species grows in evergreen forest, where it has stems that yield cane from 5 to 15m long.<ref name=\"evans\" /><ref name=\"dyphon\" />\nOccurring in the stunted-forest community, called ''for\u00eat sempervirente basse de montagne'' by [[Pauline Dy Phon]], in [[Preah Monivong National Park|Bokor National Park]], [[Kampot Province]], Cambodia, the climber grows at elevations up to 1014m.<ref name=\"rundel\">{{cite journal |last1=Rundel|first1=Philip W. |last2=Middleton |first2=David J. |title=Flora of Bokor Plateau, southeastern Cambodia: a homage to [[Pauline Dy Phon]] |journal=Cambodian Journal of Natural History |date=2017 |volume=1 |pages=17\u201337}}</ref>\nIn [[B\u1ea1ch M\u00e3 National Park]], central Vietnam, which predominantly has tropical and subtropical monsoon evergreen rainforest, it grows at elevations from 400 to 1000m, in areas of 50-60% forest cover.<ref name=\"ninh\" /> Locally the species is called \u2018alone-rattan\u2019 or \u2018faithful-rattan\u2019 because if a plant of one sex is found then a plant of the opposite sex will be nearby. The single-stemmed (not clumping) plant grows to 5-6m in the park, and is noted for its big parallelogram-shaped leaf, with a wrinkled surface and wavy border.\nSubspecies ''bousigonii'' has [[rachis]] [[bracts]] that are strictly tubular and for the most part intact, not splitting, and the first order branches are inserted at the mouth of the bracts. The ''smitinandii'' subspecies is \"one of the most attractive of all Thai rattans ... glossy undulate diamond-shaped leaflets and its neat low habit give it considerable horticultural potential[, a]mong Thai species it is very distinctive.\" John Dransfield.<ref name=\"cbss\" /> Subspecies ''smitinandii'' is a slender rattan, clustering and growing up to 10m, rarely to 20m, it often flowers and fruits at 2-3m. Its stems without sheaves are 4-8mm in diameter. The leaf sheath is densely covered in solitary spines, 1-13mm long. The bracts on the ''smitinandii'' rachis are elongate, split for at least half their length, opening out and becoming flattened and tattering; first order branches are inserted about half way along length of the bracts.\nIn peninsular Malaysia, ''Calamus'' species have different flowering seasons, a mechanism to maintain reproductive barriers or to divide pollinator resources, ''C. bousigonii'' has peak flowering in November\u2013December.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Barfod |first1=Anders S. |last2=Hagen |first2=Melanie |last3=Borchsenius |first3=Finn |title=Twenty-five years of progress in understanding pollination mechanisms in palms (Arecaceae) |journal=Annals of Botany |date=2011 |volume=108 |issue=8 |pages=1503\u201316 |url=https://academic.oup.com/aob/article/108/8/1503/160500 |accessdate=18 April 2020 |publisher=Oxford University Press}}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\nBasket making is carried on using the long cane from this palm in Cambodia.<ref name=\"dyphon\" />\nThe rattan is collected for local use in B\u1ea1ch M\u00e3 National Park, Vietnam, where the height the palms grow to demonstrates that over-harvesting is not occurring.<ref name=\"ninh\" />\nThe people in the buffer-zone of the park use rattan locally for traditional uses (construction, weaving, home-products), but it is also sold and traded, providing the second-most important source of income for poor and landless households (rice is the most important), while the majority of households use it as an income source. There has been over-exploitation of rattan sources in the area.\n\n==Note==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q15460211}}\n\n[[Category:Calamus (palm)|bousigonii]]\n[[Category:Flora of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Flora of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1902]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|image =\n|genus = Calamus (palm)\n|species = bousigonii\n|authority = [[Odoardo Beccari|Becc.]], Rec. Bot. Surv. India ii. 209 (1902)<ref>{{cite web |title=Calamus bousigonii Becc. |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/664998-1 |website=International Plant Name Index (IPNI) |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"powo\" />}}\n\n'''''Calamus bousigonii''''', is a [[liana]], a climbing plant, and part of the [[Arecaceae]], or palm, family. It is a member of the subfamily [[Calamoideae]], whose members are usually called [[rattan]]s in English,\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThis [[species]], ''Calamus bousigonii'' Becc., has 2 [[subspecies]], ''Calamus bousigonii'' subsp. ''bousigonii'' and ''Calamus bousigonii'' subsp. ''smitinandii'' [[John Dransfield|J.Dransf.]], Kew Bull. 55(3): 713 (2000)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dransfield |first1=John |title=Calamus bousigonii |journal=Kew Bulletin |date=2000 |volu